# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cinematography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cinematography/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:cinematography/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:cinematography/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:cinematography/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:cinematography/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:cinematography/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:cinematography/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:cinematography/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:cinematography/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:cinematography/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:cinematography/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:cinematography/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:cinematography/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:cinematography/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:cinematography/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:cinematography/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:cinematography/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:cinematography/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:cinematography/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:cinematography/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:cinematography/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:cinematography/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:cinematography/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:cinematography/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:cinematography/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:cinematography/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Eastman Kodak introduced 16 mm film in 1923, as a less expensive alternative to 35 mm film for amateurs.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The same year the Victor Animatograph Corporation started producing their own 16 mm cameras and projectors.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] During the 1920s, the format was often referred to by the professional industry as 'sub-standard'.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Kodak hired Willard Beech Cook from his 28 mm Pathescope of America company to create the new 16 mm 'Kodascope Library'.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In addition to making home movies, people could buy or rent films from the library, a key selling aspect of the format.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Intended for amateur use, 16 mm film was one of the first formats to use acetate safety film as a film base.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Kodak never used nitrate film for the format, owing to the high flammability of the nitrate base.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Kodak discontinued all nitrate base use in 1952.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The silent 16 mm format was initially aimed at the home enthusiast, but by the 1930s it had begun to make inroads into the educational market.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The addition of optical sound tracks and, most notably, Kodachrome in 1935, gave an enormous boost to its popularity.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The format was used extensively during World War II (*To the Shores of Iwo Jima*), and there was a huge expansion of 16 mm professional filmmaking in the post-war years.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Films for government, business, medical and industrial clients created a large network of 16 mm professional filmmakers and related service industries in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The advent of television production also enhanced the use of 16 mm film, initially for its advantage of cost and portability over 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] At first used as a news-gathering format, the 16 mm format was also used to create television programming shot outside the confines of the more rigid television studio production sets.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The home movie market gradually switched to the even less expensive 8 mm and Super 8 mm film formats.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] 16 mm, using light cameras, was extensively used for television production in many countries before portable video cameras appeared.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In Britain, the BBC's Ealing-based film department made significant use of 16mm film and, during its peak, employed over 50 film crews.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Throughout much of the 1960s–1990s period, these crews made use of cameras such as the Arriflex ST and Eclair NPR in combination with quarter-inch sound recorders, such as the Nagra III.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Using these professional tools, film department crews would work on some of the most significant programmes produced by the BBC, including *Man Alive*, *Panorama* and *Chronicle*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Usually made up of five people, these small crews were able to work incredibly efficiently and, even in hostile environments, were able to film an entire programme with a shooting ratio of less than 5:1.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Beginning in the 1950s, news organizations and documentarians in the United States frequently shot on portable Auricon and, later, CP-16 cameras that were self-blimped and had the ability to record sound directly on film.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The introduction of magnetic striped film further improved sound fidelity.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Replacing analog video devices, digital video has made significant inroads in television production use.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Nevertheless, 16 mm is still in use in its Super 16 ratio (see below) for productions seeking its specific look.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Two perforation pitches are available for 16 mm film.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] One specification, known as "long pitch", has a spacing of 7.62 mm (0.300 in) and is used primarily for print and reversal film stocks.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Negative and intermediate film stocks have perforations spaced 7.605 mm (0.2994 in), known as "short pitch".
[src:cinematography/16-mm] These differences allow for the sharpest and smoothest possible image when making prints using a contact printer.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Film stocks are available in either 'single-perf' or 'double-perf', meaning the film is perforated on either one or both edges.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The picture-taking area of standard 16 mm is 10.26 mm × 7.49 mm (0.404 in × 0.295 in), an aspect ratio of 1.37, the standard pre-widescreen Academy ratio for 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The "nominal" picture projection area (per SMPTE RP 20-2003) is 0.380 in by 0.284 in, and the maximum picture projection area (per SMPTE ST 233-2003) is 0.384 in by 0.286 in, each implying an aspect ratio of 1.34:1.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Double-perf 16 mm film, the original format, has a perforation at both sides of every frame line.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Single-perf is perforated at one side only, making room for an optical or magnetic soundtrack along the other side.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The variant called **Super 16 mm**, **Super 16**, or **16 mm Type W** is an adaptation of the 1.66 (1.66:1 or 15:9) aspect ratio of the "Paramount format" to 16 mm film.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] It was developed by Swedish cinematographer Rune Ericson in 1969, using single-sprocket film and taking advantage of the extra room for an expanded picture area of 12.52 mm × 7.41 mm (0.493 in × 0.292 in), giving an aspect ratio of 1.69.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] And, with the recent development of digital intermediate workflows, it is now possible to digitally enlarge to a 35 mm sound print with virtually no quality loss (given a high quality digital scan), or alternatively to use high-quality video equipment for the original image capture.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In 2009, German lens manufacturer Vantage introduced a series of anamorphic lenses under its HAWK brand.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] These provided a 1.30x squeeze factor (as opposed to the standard 2×) specifically for the Super 16 format, allowing nearly all of the Super 16 frame to be used for 2.39:1 widescreen photography.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The DIY-crafted **Ultra 16** is a variation of Super 16.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] DeMarco is credited with inventing Ultra 16 in 1996 while shooting tests for Darren Aronofsky's *Pi*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Ultra 16 is created by widening the left and right sides of the gate of a standard 16 mm camera by 0.7 mm to expose part of the horizontal area between the perforations.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Perforation placement on standard 16 mm film at the divisions between frames accommodates use of these normally unexposed areas.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Thus, almost all standard 16 mm optics can now achieve the wider image in Ultra 16, but without the above pitfalls and optical "shortcomings" encountered when attempting their use for Super 16.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The only suppliers of 16 mm color reversal/negative film in 2022 were Kodak and Orwo.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Agfa and Fuji closed their film manufacturing facilities in the 2010s.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] B&W films are still produced by Kodak, Foma and ORWO/Filmotec, with ORWO/Filmotec having begun sales of a new color negative film in May of 2022.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] 16 mm film is used in television, such as for the *Hallmark Hall of Fame* anthology (it has since been produced in 16:9 high definition) and *Friday Night Lights* and *The O.C.* as well as *The Walking Dead* in the US.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In the UK, the format is exceedingly popular for television series such as *Doc Martin*, dramas and commercials.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) played a large part in the development of the format.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] As of 2016, the format was frequently used for student films, while its use in documentaries had almost disappeared.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] With the advent of HDTV, Super 16 film is still used for some productions destined for HD.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Some low-budget theatrical features are shot on 16 mm and super 16 mm such as Kevin Smith's 16 mm 1994 independent hit *Clerks,* or *Man Bites Dog*, *Mid90s* and *Closer to Home*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Thanks to advances in film stock and digital technology—specifically digital intermediate (DI)—the format has dramatically improved in picture quality since the 1970s, and is now a revitalized option.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] *Vera Drake*, for example, was shot on Super 16 mm film, digitally scanned at a high resolution, edited and color graded, and then printed out onto 35 mm film via a laser film recorder.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Because of the digital process, the final 35 mm print quality is good enough to fool some professionals into thinking it was shot on 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In Britain, most exterior television footage was shot on 16 mm from the 1960s until the 1990s, when the development of more portable television cameras and videotape machines led to video replacing 16 mm in many instances.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Many drama shows and documentaries were made entirely on 16 mm, notably *Brideshead Revisited*, *The Jewel in the Crown*, *The Ascent of Man*, *Life on Earth*, and the early seasons of *Poirot*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] More recently, the advent of widescreen television has led to the use of *Super* 16.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] For example, the 2008 BBC fantasy drama series *Merlin* was shot in Super 16.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] As recently as 2010, *Scrubs* was shot on Super16 and aired either as 4:3 SD (first 7 seasons) or as 16:9 HD (seasons 8 and 9).
[src:cinematography/16-mm] John Inwood, the cinematographer of the series, believed that footage from his Aaton XTR Prod camera was not only sufficient to air in high definition, it "looked terrific".
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The Academy Award winning *Leaving Las Vegas* was shot on 16 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The first two seasons of *Buffy the Vampire Slayer* were shot on 16 mm and switched to 35 mm for its later seasons.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The first season of *Sex and the City* was shot on 16 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] All three seasons of *Veronica Mars* were shot on 16 mm and aired in HD.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] *This Is Spinal Tap*, and Christopher Guest's subsequent mockumentary films, are shot in Super 16 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The first three seasons of *Stargate SG-1* (bar the season 3 finale and the effects shots) were shot in 16 mm, before switching to 35 mm for later seasons.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Peter Jackson's 1992 zombie comedy *Braindead* was shot on Super 16mm, so that more of its $3 million budget could be spent on its extensive gore effects.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Catherine Hardwicke's 2003 teen drama *Thirteen* was shot on Super 16mm, due to low budget of $2 million.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The 2009 Academy Award winner for Best Picture, *The Hurt Locker*, was shot using Aaton Super 16 mm cameras and Fujifilm 16 mm film stocks.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The cost savings over 35 mm allowed the production to utilize multiple cameras for many shots, exposing over one million feet of film.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] British Napoleonic-era TV drama *Sharpe* was shot on Super 16 mm right through to the film *Sharpe's Challenge*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] For the last film in the series, *Sharpe's Peril*, the producers switched to 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Darren Aronofsky shot *mother!* on 16 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Linus Sandgren shot most of the 2018 biographical drama *First Man* on Super 16.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Spike Lee shot the Netflix film *Da 5 Bloods*' flashback scenes on 16 mm film, which was part of the reason cinematographer Newton Thomas Sigel was considered for an Oscar nomination.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] *The Insider* reports that Netflix was "initially concerned about having the movie's flashback scenes shot on grainy 16 mm film ...
[src:cinematography/16-mm] There was pushback because it opened up a lot of challenges." According to Sigel, the film stock Lee wanted to use was expensive because it is rarely used.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] It would be even more expensive to shoot on 16mm film while on location in Vietnam and then ship the film back to the United States to be processed at a film lab.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Cornish filmmaker Mark Jenkin is notable for using 16 mm film and a hand-cranked 1978 Bolex camera, most notably in his films *Bait* and *Enys Men*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] 16mm film was also used to produce early Full-Motion Video arcade games, such as Nintendo's *Wild Gunman* (1974) and Kasco's *The Driver* (1979).
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Independent filmmaking - Many modern creatives utilise the 16mm format in smaller independent productions such as music videos, short films and advertising.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] A number of digital cameras approximate the look of the 16 mm format by using 16 mm-sized sensors and taking 16 mm lenses.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] These cameras include the Ikonoskop A-Cam DII (2008) and the Digital Bolex (2012).
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The Blackmagic Pocket Cinema Camera (2013) and the Blackmagic Micro Cinema Camera (2015) has a Super 16-sized sensor.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The Z CAM E2G (2019) even offers Digital 16 mm in 4K and with a global shutter.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The professional industry tends to use 16 mm cameras from Aaton and Arri, most notably the Aaton Xtera, Aaton XTRprod, Arriflex 16SR3, and Arriflex 416.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Aaton also released the A-Minima, which is about the size of a video camcorder and is used for specialized filming requiring smaller, more versatile cameras.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Photo Sonics have special extremely high speed cameras for 16 mm that film at up to 1,000 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Panavision has produced the Panaflex 16, nicknamed "Elaine".
[src:cinematography/16-mm] For amateur, hobbyist, and student use, it is more economical to use older models from Arri, Aaton, Auricon, Beaulieu, Bell and Howell, Bolex, Canon, Cinema Products, Eclair, Keystone, Krasnogorsk, Mitchell, and others.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Most original movie production companies that use film shoot on 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The 35 mm size must be converted or reduced to 16 mm for 16 mm systems.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] There are multiple ways of obtaining a 16 mm print from 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The preferred method is to strike a 16 mm negative from the original 35 mm negative and then make a print from the new 16 mm negative.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] A 16 mm negative struck from the original 35 mm negative is called an *original*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] A new 16 mm print made from a print with no negative is called a *reversal*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Film traders often refer to 16 mm prints by the print's production method, i.e., an *original*, *reversal*, *dupe down*, *double dupe*, or *double dupe down*.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Over time, the cyan, magenta and yellow dyes that form the image in color 16 mm film inevitably fade.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The rate of deterioration depends on storage conditions and the film type.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In the case of Kodachrome amateur and documentary films and Technicolor IB (imbibition process) color prints, the dyes are so stable and the deterioration so slow that even prints now over 70 years old typically show no obvious problems.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Dyes in the far more common Eastmancolor print film and similar products from other manufacturers are notoriously unstable.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] Prior to the introduction of a longer-lasting "low fade" type in 1979, Eastmancolor prints routinely suffered from easily seen color shift and fading within ten years.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] The dyes degrade at different rates, with magenta being the longest-lasting, eventually resulting in a pale reddish image with little if any other color discernible.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] In the process of digitizing old color films, even badly faded source material can sometimes be restored to full color through digital techniques that amplify the faded dye colors.
[src:cinematography/16-mm] A digital intermediate scanned from the original negative (if it was processed and stored correctly) can often fully restore colors.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The basic components of 3D film were introduced separately between 1833 and 1839.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Stroboscopic animation was developed by Joseph Plateau in 1832 and published in 1833 in the form of a stroboscopic disc, which he later called the fantascope and became better known as the phénakisticope.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Around the very same time (1832/1833), Charles Wheatstone developed the stereoscope, but he did not really make it public before June 1838.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The first practical forms of photography were introduced in January 1839 by Louis Daguerre and Henry Fox Talbot.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] A combination of these elements into animated stereoscopic photography may have been conceived early on, but for decades it did not become possible to capture motion in real-time photographic recordings due to the long exposure times necessary for the light-sensitive emulsions that were used.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Charles Wheatstone got inventor Henry Fox Talbot to produce some calotype pairs for the stereoscope and received the first results in October 1840.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Only a few more experimental stereoscopic photographs were made before David Brewster introduced his stereoscope with lenses in 1849.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Wheatstone also approached Joseph Plateau with the suggestion to combine the stereoscope with the fantascope.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1849, Plateau published about this concept in an article about several improvements made to his fantascope and suggested a stop-motion technique that would involve a series of photographs of purpose-made plaster statuettes in different poses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The idea reached Jules Duboscq, an instrument maker who already marketed Plateau's Fantascope as well as the stereoscopes of Wheatstone and Brewster.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In November 1852, Duboscq added the concept of his "Stéréoscope-fantascope, ou Bïoscope" to his stereoscope patent.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Production of images proved very difficult, since the photographic sequence had to be carefully constructed from separate still images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The bioscope was no success, and the only extant disc, without apparatus, is found in the Joseph Plateau collection of the University of Ghent.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The disc contains 12 albumen image pairs of a machine in motion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Most other early attempts to create motion pictures also aimed to include stereoscopic effects.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In November 1851, Antoine Claudet claimed to have created a stereoscope that showed people in motion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The device initially only showed two phases, but during the next two years, Claudet worked on a camera that would record stereoscopic pairs for four different poses (patented in 1853).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Claudet found that the stereoscopic effect did not work properly in this device, but believed the illusion of motion was successful.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1855, Johann Nepomuk Czermak published an article about his Stereophoroskop.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] His first idea to create 3D animation involved sticking pins in a stroboscopic disc to create a sequence that would show one pin moving further into the cardboard and back.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] He also designed a device that would feed the image pairs from two stroboscopic discs into one lenticular stereoscope and a vertical predecessor of the zoetrope.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] On February 27, 1860, Peter Hubert Desvignes received British patent no.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] 537 for 28 monocular and stereoscopic variations of cylindrical stroboscopic devices.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] This included a version that used an endless band of pictures running between two spools that was intermittently lit by an electric spark.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Desvignes' *Mimoscope*, received an Honourable Mention "for ingenuity of construction" at the 1862 International Exhibition in London.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1861, American engineer Coleman Sellers II received US patent No.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] 35,317 for the kinematoscope, a device that exhibited "stereoscopic pictures as to make them represent objects in motion".
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In his application he stated: "This has frequently been done with plane pictures but has never been, with stereoscopic pictures".
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] He used three sets of stereoscopic photographs in a sequence with some duplicates to regulate the flow of a simple repetitive motion, but also described a system for very large series of pictures of complicated motion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] On August 11, 1877, the *Daily Alta* newspaper announced a project by Eadward Muybridge and Leland Stanford to produce sequences of photographs of a running horse with 12 stereoscopic cameras.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Muybridge had much experience with stereo photography and had already made instantaneous pictures of Stanford's horse Occident running at full speed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] He eventually managed to shoot the proposed sequences of running horses in June 1878 with stereoscopic cameras.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Thomas Edison demonstrated his phonograph on November 29, 1877, after previous announcements of the device for recording and replaying sound had been published earlier in the year.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] An article in *Scientific American* concluded, "It is already possible, by ingenious optical contrivances, to throw stereoscopic photographs of people on screens in full view of an audience.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Add the talking phonograph to counterfeit their voices, and it would be difficult to carry the illusion of real presence much further".
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Wordsworth Donisthorpe announced in the January 24, 1878, edition of *Nature* that he would advance that conception: "By combining the phonograph with the kinesigraph, I will undertake not only to produce a talking picture of Mr.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Gladstone, which, with motionless lips and unchanged expression, shall positively recite his latest anti-Turkish speech in his own voice and tone.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Not only this, but the life size photograph itself shall move and gesticulate precisely as he did when making the speech, the words and gestures corresponding as in real life." Dr.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Phipson, a correspondent for British news in a French photography magazine, relayed the concept but renamed the device "Kinétiscope" to reflect the viewing purpose rather than the recording option.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] This was picked up in the United States and discussed in an interview with Edison later in the year.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Neither Donisthorpe's nor Edison's later moving picture results were stereoscopic.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In the late 1890s, British film pioneer William Friese-Greene filed a patent for a 3D film process.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In his patent, two films were projected side by side on screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The viewer looked through a stereoscope to converge the two images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Because of the obtrusive mechanics behind this method, theatrical use was not practical.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Frederic Eugene Ives patented his stereo camera rig in 1900.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The camera had two lenses positioned 1+3⁄4 inches (4.45 centimeters) apart.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Waddell presented tests to an audience at the Astor Theater in New York City.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] However, according to Adolph Zukor in his 1953 autobiography *The Public Is Never Wrong: My 50 Years in the Motion Picture Industry*, nothing was produced in this process after these tests.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] By 1909, the German film market suffered much from overproduction and too much competition.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] German film tycoon Oskar Messter had initially gained much financial success with the Tonbild synchronized sound films of his Biophon system since 1903, but the films were losing money by the end of the decade, and Messter would stop Tonbild production in 1913.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Producers and exhibitors were looking into new film attractions and invested for instance in colorful imagery.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The development of stereoscopic cinema seemed a logical step to lure visitors back into the movie theaters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1909, German civil engineer August Engelsmann patented a process that projected filmed performances within a physical decor on an actual stage.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Soon after, Messter obtained patents for a very similar process, probably by agreement with Engelsmann, and started marketing it as "Alabastra".
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Performers were brightly dressed and brightly lit while filmed against a black background, mostly miming their singing or musical skills or dancing to the circa four-minute pre-recorded phonographs.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The film recordings would be projected from below, to appear as circa 30 inch figures on a glass pane in front of a small stage, in a setup very similar to the Pepper's ghost illusion that offered a popular stage trick technique since the 1860s.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The glass pane was not visible to the audience and the projected figures seemed able to move around freely across the stage in their virtual tangible and lifelike appearance.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The brightness of the figures was necessary to avoid see-through spots and made them resemble alabaster sculptures.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] To adapt to this appearance, several films featured Pierrot or other white clowns, while some films were probably hand-coloured.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Although Alabastra was well received by the press, Messter produced few titles, hardly promoted them and abandoned it altogether a few years later.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] He believed the system to be uneconomical due to its need for special theatres instead of the widely available movie screens, and he did not like that it seemed only suitable for stage productions and not for "natural" films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Nonetheless, there were numerous imitators in Germany and Messter and Engelsmann still teamed with American businessman Frank Joseph Godsol (Goldsoll) set up a short-lived variant named "Fantomo" in 1914.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Rather in agreement with Messter or not, Karl Juhasz and Franz Haushofer opened a Kinoplastikon theatre in Vienna in 1911.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Their patented system was very similar to Alabaster, but projected life-size figures from the wings of the stage.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] With much higher ticket prices than standard cinema, it was targeted at middle-class audiences to fill the gap between low-brow films and high-class theatre.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Audiences reacted enthusiastically and by 1913 there reportedly were 250 theatres outside Austria, in France, Italy, United Kingdom, Russia and North America.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] However, the first Kinoplastikon in Paris started in January 1914 and the premiere in New York took place in the Hippodrome in March 1915.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Kinoplastikon, presumably in collaboration with Cecil Hepworth.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Theodore Brown, the licensee in the U.K. also patented a variant with front and back projection and reflected decor, and Goldsoll applied for a very similar patent only 10 days later.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Further development and exploitation was probably halted by World War I.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Alabastra and Kinoplastikon were often advertised as stereoscopic and screenless.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Eventually, longer (multi-reel) films with story arcs proved to be the way out of the crisis in the movie market and supplanted the previously popular short films that mostly aimed to amuse people with tricks, gags or other brief variety and novelty attractions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Sound film, stereoscopic film and other novel techniques were relatively cumbersome to combine with multiple reels and were abandoned for a while.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The earliest confirmed 3D film shown to an out-of-house audience was *The Power of Love*, which premiered at the Ambassador Hotel Theater in Los Angeles on September 27, 1922.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The camera rig was a product of the film's producer, Harry K.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] It was filmed dual-strip in black and white, and single strip color anaglyphic release prints were produced using a color film invented and patented by Harry K.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] A single projector could be used to display the movie but anaglyph glasses were used for viewing.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The camera system and special color release print film all received U.S Patent No.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] After a preview for exhibitors and press in New York City, the film dropped out of sight, apparently not booked by exhibitors, and is now considered lost.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Early in December 1922, William Van Doren Kelley, inventor of the Prizma color system, cashed in on the growing interest in 3D films started by Fairall's demonstration and shot footage with a camera system of his own design.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Kelley then struck a deal with Samuel "Roxy" Rothafel to premiere the first in his series of "Plasticon" shorts entitled *Movies of the Future* at the Rivoli Theater in New York City.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Also in December 1922, Laurens Hammond (later inventor of the Hammond organ) premiered his Teleview system, which had been shown to the trade and press in October.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Teleview was the first alternating-frame 3D system seen by the public.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Using left-eye and right-eye prints and two interlocked projectors, left and right frames were alternately projected, each pair being shown three times to suppress flicker.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Viewing devices attached to the armrests of the theater seats had rotary shutters that operated synchronously with the projector shutters, producing a clean and clear stereoscopic result.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The only theater known to have installed Teleview was the Selwyn Theater in New York City, and only one show was ever presented with it: a group of short films, an exhibition of live 3D shadows, and *M.A.R.S.*, the only Teleview feature.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The show ran for several weeks, apparently doing good business as a novelty (*M.A.R.S.* itself got poor reviews), but Teleview was never seen again.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1922, Frederic Eugene Ives and Jacob Leventhal began releasing their first stereoscopic shorts made over a three-year period.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The first film, entitled *Plastigrams*, was distributed nationally by Educational Pictures in the red-and-blue anaglyph format.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Ives and Leventhal then went on to produce the following stereoscopic shorts in the "Stereoscopiks Series" released by Pathé Films in 1925: *Zowie* (April 10), *Luna-cy!* (May 18), *The Run-Away Taxi* (December 17) and *Ouch* (December 17).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] On September 22, 1924, *Luna-cy!* was re-released in the De Forest Phonofilm sound-on-film system.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The late 1920s to early 1930s saw little interest in stereoscopic pictures.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In Paris, Louis Lumiere shot footage with his stereoscopic camera in September 1933.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The following March he exhibited a remake of his 1895 short film *L'Arrivée du Train*, this time in anaglyphic 3D, at a meeting of the French Academy of Science.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1936, Leventhal and John Norling were hired based on their test footage to film MGM's *Audioscopiks* series.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The prints were by Technicolor in the red-and-green anaglyph format, and were narrated by Pete Smith.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The first film, *Audioscopiks*, premiered January 11, 1936, and *The New Audioscopiks* premiered January 15, 1938.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] *Audioscopiks* was nominated for the Academy Award in the category Best Short Subject, Novelty in 1936.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] With the success of the two Audioscopiks films, MGM produced one more short in anaglyph 3D, another Pete Smith Specialty called *Third Dimensional Murder* (1941).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Unlike its predecessors, this short was shot with a studio-built camera rig.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Prints were by Technicolor in red-and-blue anaglyph.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The short is notable for being one of the few live-action appearances of the Frankenstein Monster as conceived by Jack Pierce for Universal Studios outside of their company.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] While many of these films were printed by color systems, none of them was actually in color, and the use of the color printing was only to achieve an anaglyph effect.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] While attending Harvard University, Edwin H.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Land conceived the idea of reducing glare by polarizing light.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] He took a leave of absence from Harvard to set up a lab and by 1929 had invented and patented a polarizing sheet.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1932, he introduced **Polaroid J Sheet** as a commercial product.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] While his original intention was to create a filter for reducing glare from car headlights, Land did not underestimate the utility of his newly dubbed Polaroid filters in stereoscopic presentations.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In February 1936, Land gave the first public demonstration of Polaroid filters in conjunction with 3D photography at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The reaction was enthusiastic, and Land followed it up with an installation at the New York Museum of Science.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] It is unknown what film was run for audiences at this exhibition.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Using Polaroid filters meant an entirely new form of projection, however.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Two prints, each carrying either the right or left eye view, had to be synced up in projection using an external selsyn motor.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Furthermore, polarized light would be largely depolarized by a matte white screen, and only a silver screen or screen made of other reflective material would correctly reflect the separate images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Later that year, the feature, *Nozze Vagabonde* appeared in Italy, followed in Germany by *Zum Greifen nah* (*You Can Nearly Touch It*), and again in 1939 with Germany's *Sechs Mädel rollen ins Wochenend* (*Six Girls Drive Into the Weekend*).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The Italian film was made with the Gualtierotti camera; the two German productions with the Zeiss camera and the Vierling shooting system.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] All of these films were the first exhibited using Polaroid filters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The Zeiss Company in Germany manufactured glasses on a commercial basis commencing in 1936; they were also independently made around the same time in Germany by E.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1939, John Norling shot *In Tune With Tomorrow*, the first commercial 3D film using Polaroid in the US.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] This short premiered at the 1939 New York World's Fair and was created specifically for the Chrysler Motors Pavilion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In it, a full 1939 Chrysler Plymouth is magically put together, set to music.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Originally in black and white, the film was so popular that it was re-shot in color for the following year at the fair, under the title *New Dimensions*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In 1953, it was reissued by RKO as *Motor Rhythm*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Another early short that utilized the Polaroid 3D process was 1940's *Magic Movies: Thrills For You* produced by the Pennsylvania Railroad Co. for the Golden Gate International Exposition.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Produced by John Norling, it was filmed by Jacob Leventhal using his own rig.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] It consisted of shots of various views that could be seen from the Pennsylvania Railroad's trains.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] In the 1940s, World War II prioritized military applications of stereoscopic photography and it once again went on the back burner in most producers' minds.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] What aficionados consider the "golden era" of 3D began in late 1952 with the release of the first color stereoscopic feature, *Bwana Devil*, produced, written and directed by Arch Oboler.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The film was shot in "Natural Vision", a process that was co-created and controlled by M.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Gunzberg, who built the rig with his brother Julian, Friend Baker and Lothrop Worth, shopped it without success to various studios before Oboler used it for this feature, which went into production with the title, *The Lions of Gulu*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The critically panned film was nevertheless highly successful with audiences due to the novelty of 3D, which increased Hollywood interest in 3D during a period that had seen declining box-office admissions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] As with practically all of the features made during this boom, *Bwana Devil* was projected dual-strip, with Polaroid filters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] During the 1950s, the familiar disposable anaglyph glasses made of cardboard were mainly used for comic books, two shorts by exploitation specialist Dan Sonney, and three shorts produced by Lippert Productions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] However, even the Lippert shorts were available in the dual-strip format alternatively.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Because the features utilized two projectors, the capacity limit of film being loaded onto each projector (about 6,000 feet (1,800 m), or an hour's worth of film) meant that an intermission was necessary for every feature-length film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Quite often, intermission points were written into the script at a major plot point.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] During Christmas of 1952, producer Sol Lesser quickly premiered the dual-strip showcase called *Stereo Techniques* in Chicago.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Lesser acquired the rights to five dual-strip shorts.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Two of them, *Now is the Time (to Put On Your Glasses)* and *Around is Around*, were directed by Norman McLaren in 1951 for the National Film Board of Canada.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The other three films were produced in Britain for The Festival of Britain in 1951 by Raymond Spottiswoode.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] These were *A Solid Explanation*, *Royal River*, and *The Black Swan*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] James Mage was also an early pioneer in the 3D craze.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Using his 16 mm 3D Bolex system, he premiered his *Triorama* program on February 10, 1953, with his four shorts: *Sunday In Stereo*, *Indian Summer*, *American Life*, and *This is Bolex Stereo*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Another early 3D film during the boom was the Lippert Productions short *A Day in the Country*, narrated by Joe Besser, which was composed mostly of test footage.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Unlike all of the other Lippert shorts, which were available in both dual-strip and anaglyph, this production was released in anaglyph only.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] April 1953 saw two groundbreaking features in 3D: Columbia's *Man in the Dark* and Warner Bros.' *House of Wax*, the first 3D feature with stereophonic sound.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The success of these two films proved that major studios now had a method of getting filmgoers back into theaters and away from television sets, which were causing a steady decline in attendance.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Universal-International released its first 3D feature, *It Came from Outer Space*, on May 27, 1953, with stereophonic sound.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] That was followed by Paramount's first 3D feature, *Sangaree* with Fernando Lamas and Arlene Dahl.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The Walt Disney Studios entered 3D with its May 28, 1953, release of *Melody*, which accompanied the first 3D western, Columbia's *Fort Ti* at its Los Angeles opening.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] It was later shown at Disneyland's Fantasyland Theater in 1957 as part of a program with Disney's other short *Working for Peanuts*, entitled, *3-D Jamboree*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The show was hosted by the Mousketeers and was in color.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Columbia released several 3D westerns produced by Sam Katzman and directed by William Castle.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Castle would later specialize in various technical in-theater gimmicks for such Columbia and Allied Artists features as *13 Ghosts*, *House on Haunted Hill*, and *The Tingler*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Columbia also produced the only slapstick comedies conceived for 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The Three Stooges starred in *Spooks* and *Pardon My Backfire*; dialect comic Harry Mimmo starred in *Down the Hatch*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Producer Jules White was optimistic about the possibilities of 3D as applied to slapstick (with pies and other projectiles aimed at the audience), but only two of his stereoscopic shorts were shown in 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] *Down the Hatch* was released as a conventional, "flat" motion picture.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] John Ireland, Joanne Dru and Macdonald Carey starred in the Jack Broder color production *Hannah Lee*, which premiered on June 19, 1953.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The film was directed by Ireland, who sued Broder for his salary.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Broder counter-sued, claiming that Ireland went over production costs with the film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Another famous entry in the golden era of 3D was the 3 Dimensional Pictures production of *Robot Monster*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The film was allegedly scribed in an hour by screenwriter Wyott Ordung and filmed in a period of two weeks on a shoestring budget.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Despite these shortcomings and the fact that the crew had no previous experience with the newly built camera rig, luck was on the cinematographer's side, as many find the 3D photography in the film is well shot and aligned.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] *Robot Monster* also has a notable score by then up-and-coming composer Elmer Bernstein.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The film was released June 24, 1953, and went out with the short *Stardust in Your Eyes*, which starred nightclub comedian, Slick Slavin.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] 20th Century Fox produced its only 3D feature, *Inferno*, in 1953, starring Rhonda Fleming.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Fleming, who also starred in *Those Redheads From Seattle*, and *Jivaro*, shares the spot for being the actress to appear in the most 3D features with Patricia Medina, who starred in *Sangaree*, *Phantom of the Rue Morgue* and *Drums of Tahiti*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] Zanuck expressed little interest in stereoscopic systems, and at that point was preparing to premiere the new widescreen film system, CinemaScope.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p01] The first decline in the theatrical 3D craze started in August and September 1953.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Sol Lesser attempted to follow up *Stereo Techniques* with a new showcase, this time five shorts that he himself produced.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The project was to be called *The 3-D Follies* and was to be distributed by RKO.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Unfortunately, because of financial difficulties and the general loss of interest in 3D, Lesser canceled the project during the summer of 1953, making it the first 3D film to be aborted in production.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Two of the three shorts were shot: *Carmenesque*, a burlesque number starring exotic dancer Lili St.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Cyr, and *Fun in the Sun*, a sports short directed by famed set designer/director William Cameron Menzies, who also directed the 3D feature *The Maze* for Allied Artists.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Although it was more expensive to install, the major competing realism process was wide-screen, but two-dimensional, anamorphic, first utilized by Fox with CinemaScope and its September premiere in *The Robe*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Anamorphic films needed only a single print, so synchronization was not an issue.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Cinerama was also a competitor from the start and had better quality control than 3D because it was owned by one company that focused on quality control.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] However, most of the 3D features past the summer of 1953 were released in the flat widescreen formats ranging from 1.66:1 to 1.85:1.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In early studio advertisements and articles about widescreen and 3D formats, widescreen systems were referred to as "3D", causing some confusion among scholars.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] There was no single instance of combining CinemaScope with 3D until 1960, with a film called *September Storm*, and even then, that was a blow-up from a non-anamorphic negative.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *September Storm* also went out with the last dual-strip short, *Space Attack*, which was actually shot in 1954 under the title *The Adventures of Sam Space*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In December 1953, 3D made a comeback with the release of several important 3D films, including MGM's musical *Kiss Me, Kate*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Kate* was the hill over which 3D had to pass to survive.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] MGM tested it in six theaters: three in 3D and three-flat.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] According to trade ads of the time, the 3D version was so well-received that the film quickly went into a wide stereoscopic release.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] However, most publications, including Kenneth Macgowan's classic film reference book *Behind the Screen*, state that the film did much better as a "regular" release.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The film, adapted from the popular Cole Porter Broadway musical, starred the MGM songbird team of Howard Keel and Kathryn Grayson as the leads, supported by Ann Miller, Keenan Wynn, Bobby Van, James Whitmore, Kurt Kasznar and Tommy Rall.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The film also prominently promoted its use of stereophonic sound.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Several other features that helped put 3D back on the map that month were the John Wayne feature *Hondo* (distributed by Warner Bros.), Columbia's *Miss Sadie Thompson* with Rita Hayworth, and Paramount's *Money From Home* with Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Paramount also released the cartoon shorts *Boo Moon* with Casper, the Friendly Ghost and *Popeye, Ace of Space* with Popeye the Sailor.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Paramount Pictures released a 3D Korean War film *Cease Fire* filmed on actual Korean locations in 1953.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A string of successful films filmed in 3D followed the second wave, but many were widely or exclusively shown flat.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] 3D's final decline was in the late spring of 1954, for the same reasons as the previous lull, as well as the further success of widescreen formats with theater operators.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Even though Polaroid had created a well-designed "Tell-Tale Filter Kit" for the purpose of recognizing and adjusting out of sync and phase 3D, exhibitors still felt uncomfortable with the system and turned their focus instead to processes such as CinemaScope.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The last 3D feature to be released in that format during the "Golden era" was *Revenge of the Creature*, on February 23, 1955.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Ironically, the film had a wide release in 3D and was well received at the box office.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Stereoscopic films largely remained dormant for the first part of the 1960s, with those that were released usually being anaglyph exploitation films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One film of notoriety was the Beaver-Champion/Warner Bros. production, *The Mask* (1961).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The film was shot in 2-D, but to enhance the bizarre qualities of the dream-world that is induced when the main character puts on a cursed tribal mask, these scenes went to anaglyph 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] These scenes were printed by Technicolor on their first run in red/green anaglyph.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Although 3D films appeared sparsely during the early 1960s, the true second wave of 3D cinema was set into motion by Arch Oboler, the producer who had started the craze of the 1950s.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Using a new technology called *Space-Vision 3D*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The origin of "Space-Vision 3D" goes back to Colonel Robert Vincent Bernier, a forgotten innovator in the history of stereoscopic motion pictures.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] His Trioptiscope Space-Vision lens was the gold standard for the production and exhibition of 3-D films for nearly 30 years.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] "Space-Vision 3D" stereoscopic films were printed with two images, one above the other, in a single academy ratio frame, on a single strip, and needed only one projector fitted with a special lens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This so-called "over and under" technique eliminated the need for dual projector set-ups, and produced widescreen, but darker, less vivid, polarized 3D images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Unlike earlier dual system, it could stay in perfect synchronization, unless improperly spliced in repair.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Arch Oboler once again had the vision for the system that no one else would touch, and put it to use on his film entitled *The Bubble*, which starred Michael Cole, Deborah Walley, and Johnny Desmond.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] As with *Bwana Devil*, the critics panned *The Bubble*, but audiences flocked to see it, and it became financially sound enough to promote the use of the system to other studios, particularly independents, who did not have the money for expensive dual-strip prints of their productions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 1970, Stereovision, a new entity founded by director/inventor Allan Silliphant and optical designer Chris Condon, developed a different 35 mm single-strip format, which printed two images squeezed side by side and used an anamorphic lens to widen the pictures through Polaroid filters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Sher (Sherpix) and Stereovision released the softcore sex comedy *The Stewardesses* (self-rated X, but later re-rated R by the MPAA).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Some 36 films worldwide were made with Stereovision over 25 years, using either a widescreen (above-below), anamorphic (side by side) or 70 mm 3D formats.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2009 *The Stewardesses* was remastered by Chris Condon and director Ed Meyer, releasing it in XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The quality of the 1970s 3D films was not much more inventive, as many were either softcore and even hardcore adult films, horror films, or a combination of both.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Paul Morrisey's *Flesh For Frankenstein* (aka *Andy Warhol's Frankenstein*) was a superlative example of such a combination.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Between 1981 and 1983 there was a new Hollywood 3D craze started by the spaghetti western *Comin' at Ya!*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] When *Parasite* was released it was billed as the first horror film to come out in 3D in over 20 years.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Horror films and reissues of 1950s 3D classics (such as Hitchcock's *Dial M for Murder*) dominated the 3D releases that followed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The second sequel in the *Friday the 13th* series, *Friday the 13th Part III*, was released very successfully.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Apparently saying "part 3 in 3D" was considered too cumbersome so it was shortened in the titles of *Jaws 3-D* and *Amityville 3-D*, which emphasized the screen effects to the point of being annoying at times, especially when flashlights were shone into the eyes of the audience.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The science fiction film *Spacehunter: Adventures in the Forbidden Zone* was the most expensive 3D film made up to that point with production costs about the same as *Star Wars* but not nearly the same box office success, causing the craze to fade quickly through spring 1983.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Other sci-fi/fantasy films were released as well including *Metalstorm: The Destruction of Jared-Syn* and *Treasure of the Four Crowns*, which was widely criticized for poor editing and plot holes, but did feature some truly spectacular closeups.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] 3D releases after the second craze included *The Man Who Wasn't There* (1983), *Silent Madness* and the 1985 animated film *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*, whose plot seemed to borrow heavily from *Star Wars*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Only *Comin' At Ya!*, *Parasite*, and *Friday the 13th Part III* have been officially released on VHS and/or DVD in 3D in the United States (although *Amityville 3D* has seen a 3D DVD release in the United Kingdom).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Most of the 1980s 3D films and some of the classic 1950s films such as *House of Wax* were released on the now defunct Video Disc (VHD) format in Japan as part of a system that used shutter glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Most of these have been unofficially transferred to DVD and are available on the grey market through sites such as eBay.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Stereoscopic movies were also popular in other parts of the world, such as My Dear Kuttichathan, a Malayalam film which was shot with stereoscopic 3D and released in 1984.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the mid-1980s, IMAX began producing non-fiction films for its nascent 3D business, starting with *We Are Born of Stars* (Roman Kroitor, 1985).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A key point was that this production, as with all subsequent IMAX productions, emphasized mathematical correctness of the 3D rendition and thus largely eliminated the eye fatigue and pain that resulted from the approximate geometries of previous 3D incarnations.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In addition, and in contrast to previous 35mm-based 3D presentations, the very large field of view provided by IMAX allowed a much broader 3D "stage", arguably as important in 3D film as it is theatre.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The Walt Disney Company also began more prominent use of 3D films in special venues to impress audiences with Magic Journeys (1982) and *Captain EO* (Francis Ford Coppola, 1986, starring Michael Jackson) being notable examples.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the same year, the National Film Board of Canada production *Transitions* (Colin Low), created for Expo 86 in Vancouver, was the first IMAX presentation using polarized glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Echoes of the Sun* (Roman Kroitor, 1990) was the first IMAX film to be presented using alternate-eye shutterglass technology, a development required because the dome screen precluded the use of polarized technology.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] From 1990 onward, numerous films were produced by all three parties to satisfy the demands of their various high-profile special attractions and IMAX's expanding 3D network.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Films of special note during this period include the extremely successful *Into the Deep* (Graeme Ferguson, 1995) and the first IMAX 3D fiction film *Wings of Courage* (1996), by director Jean-Jacques Annaud, about the pilot Henri Guillaumet.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] By 2004, 54% of IMAX theaters (133 of 248) were capable of showing 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Shortly thereafter, higher quality computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, digital video capture, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70mm film projectors, created an opportunity for another wave of 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2003, *Ghosts of the Abyss* by James Cameron was released as the first full-length 3D IMAX feature filmed with the Reality Camera System.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This camera system used the latest HD video cameras, not film, and was built for Cameron by Vince Pace, to his specifications.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The same camera system was used to film *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over* (2003), *Aliens of the Deep* IMAX (2005), and *The Adventures of Sharkboy and Lavagirl in 3-D* (2005).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2004, Las Vegas Hilton released Star Trek: The Experience which included two films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One of the films, *Borg Invasion 4-D* (Ty Granoroli), was in 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In August of the same year, rap group Insane Clown Posse released their ninth studio album *Hell's Pit*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One of two versions of the album contained a DVD featuring a 3D short film for the track "Bowling Balls", shot in high-definition video.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In November 2004, *The Polar Express* was released as IMAX's first full-length, animated 3D feature.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It was released in 3,584 theaters in 2D, and only 66 IMAX locations.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The return from those few 3D theaters was about 25% of the total.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The 3D version earned about 14 times as much per screen as the 2D version.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This pattern continued and prompted a greatly intensified interest in 3D and 3D presentation of animated films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In June 2005, the Mann's Chinese 6 theatre in Hollywood became the first commercial film theatre to be equipped with the Digital 3D format.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Both *Singin' in the Rain* and *The Polar Express* were tested in the Digital 3D format over the course of several months.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Ben Walters suggested in 2009 that both filmmakers and film exhibitors regain interest in 3D film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] There was more 3D exhibition equipment, and more dramatic films being shot in 3D format.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One incentive is that the technology is more mature.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Shooting in 3D format is less limited, and the result is more stable.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Another incentive was the fact that while 2D ticket sales were in an overall state of decline, revenues from 3D tickets continued to grow at the time.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Through the entire history of 3D presentations, techniques to convert existing 2D images for 3D presentation have existed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The combination of digital and digitized source material with relatively cost-effective digital post-processing has spawned a new wave of conversion products.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In June 2006, IMAX and Warner Bros. released *Superman Returns* including 20 minutes of 3D images converted from the 2D original digital footage.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] George Lucas announced that he would re-release his *Star Wars* films in 3D based on a conversion process from the company In-Three.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Later on in 2011, it was announced that Lucas was working with the company Prime Focus on this conversion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In late 2005, Steven Spielberg told the press he was involved in patenting a 3D cinema system that did not need glasses, based on plasma screens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A computer splits each film-frame, and then projects the two split images onto the screen at differing angles, to be picked up by tiny angled ridges on the screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Animated films *Open Season*, and *The Ant Bully*, were released in analog 3D in 2006.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Monster House* and *The Nightmare Before Christmas* were released on XpanD 3D, RealD 3D and Dolby 3D systems in 2006.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] On May 19, 2007 *Scar3D* opened at the Cannes Film Market.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It was the first US-produced 3D full-length feature film to be completed in RealD 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It has been the #1 film at the box office in several countries around the world, including Russia where it opened in 3D on 295 screens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] On January 19, 2008, U2 3D was released; it was the first live-action digital 3D film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the same year others 3D films included *Hannah Montana & Miley Cyrus: Best of Both Worlds Concert*, *Journey to the Center of the Earth*, and *Bolt*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] On January 16, 2009, Lionsgate released *My Bloody Valentine 3D*, the first horror film and first R-rated film to be projected in RealD 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It was released to 1,033 3D screens, the most ever for this format, and 1,501 regular screens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Another R-rated film, *The Final Destination*, was released later that year in August on even more screens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It was the first of its series to be released in HD 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Major 3D films in 2009 included *Coraline*, *Monsters vs.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Aliens*, *Up*, *X Games 3D: The Movie*, *The Final Destination*, *Disney's A Christmas Carol*, and *Avatar*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Avatar* has gone on to be one of the most expensive films of all time, with a budget at $237 million; it is also the highest-grossing film of all time.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The main technologies used to exhibit these films, and many others released around the time and up to the present, are RealD 3D, Dolby 3D, XpanD 3D, MasterImage 3D, and IMAX 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The success of the film also led to electronics manufacturers releasing 3D televisions and caused 3D films to increase in popularity.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] March and April 2010 saw three major 3D releases clustered together, with *Alice in Wonderland* hitting US theaters on March 5, 2010, *How to Train Your Dragon* on March 26, 2010, and *Clash of the Titans* on April 2, 2010.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] On May 13 of the same year, China's first IMAX 3D film started shooting.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The pre-production of the first 3D film shot in France, *Derrière les murs*, began in May 2010 and was released in mid-2011.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] On October 1, 2010 *Scar3D* was the first-ever stereoscopic 3D Video-on-demand film released through major cable broadcasters for 3D televisions in the United States.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Released in the United States on May 21, 2010, *Shrek Forever After* by DreamWorks Animation (Paramount Pictures) used the RealD 3D system, also released in IMAX 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In September 2003, Sabucat Productions organized the first World 3-D Exposition, celebrating the 50th anniversary of the original craze.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The Expo was held at Grauman's Egyptian Theatre.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In attendance were many stars from each film, respectively, and some were moved to tears by the sold-out seating with audiences of film buffs from all over the world who came to remember their previous glories.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In May 2006, the second World 3-D Exposition was announced for September of that year, presented by the 3-D Film Preservation Fund.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Along with the favorites of the previous exposition were newly discovered features and shorts, and like the previous Expo, guests from each film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Expo II was announced as being the locale for the world premiere of several films never before seen in 3D, including *The Diamond Wizard* and the Universal short, *Hawaiian Nights* with Mamie Van Doren and Pinky Lee.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Other "re-premieres" of films not seen since their original release in stereoscopic form included *Cease Fire!*, *Taza, Son of Cochise*, *Wings of the Hawk*, and *Those Redheads From Seattle*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Also shown were the long-lost shorts *Carmenesque* and *A Day in the Country* (both 1953) and William Van Doren Kelley's two *Plasticon* shorts (1922 and 1923).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the wake of its initial popularity and corresponding increase in the number of screens, more films were being released in the 3D format, yet fewer people were choosing to see them in such a way.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] For instance, only 45% of the premiere weekend box office earnings of *Kung Fu Panda 2* in 2011 came from 3D screenings as opposed to 60% for *Shrek Forever After* in 2010.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In addition, the premiere of *Cars 2* opening weekend gross consisted of only 37% from 3D theatres.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 2* and *Captain America: The First Avenger* were major releases that achieved similar percentages: 43% and 40% respectively.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In view of this trend, there has been box office analysis concluding the implementation of 3D presentation is apparently backfiring by discouraging people from going to film theatres at all.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] As Brandon Gray of Box Office Mojo notes, "In each case, 3D's more-money-from-fewer-people approach has simply led to less money from even fewer people." Parallel, the number of televisions sold with support for 3D television has dropped, let alone those sold with actual 3D goggles.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] According to the Motion Picture Association of America, despite a record total of 47 3D films being released in 2011, the overall domestic box office receipts were down 18% to $1.8 billion from $2.2 billion in 2010.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Although revenues as a whole increased during 2012, the bulk has so far come from 2D presentations as exemplified by little over 50% of filmgoers opting to see the likes of *The Avengers* and 32% choosing *Brave* in their 3D versions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Conflicting reasons are respectively offered by studios and exhibitors: whereas the former blame more expensive 3D ticket prices, the latter argue that the quality of films in general is at fault.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] However, despite the perceived decline of 3D in the U.S. market, studio chiefs in 2012 were optimistic of better receipts internationally, where there still appeared to be a strong appetite for the format.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Studios are also using 3D to generate additional income from films that are already commercially successful.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Such re-releases usually involve a conversion from 2D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] For example, Disney has reissued both *The Lion King* and *Beauty and the Beast*, with plans to add some of its other well-known titles.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Titanic* has also been modified for 3D, and there are also plans to similarly present all six *Star Wars* films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Jeffrey Katzenberg, a producer of 3D films and one of the leading proponents of the format, blames oversaturation of the market with inferior films, especially ones photographed conventionally and then digitally processed in post-production.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] He claims that such films have led audiences to conclude that the format is not worth the often much higher ticket price.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Daniel Engber, a columnist for *Slate*, comes to a similar conclusion: "What happened to 3-D?
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Film critic Mark Kermode, a noted detractor of 3D, has surmised that there is an emerging policy of distributors to limit the availability of 2D versions, thus "railroading" the 3D format into cinemas whether the paying filmgoer likes it or not.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This was especially prevalent during the release of *Prometheus* in 2012, where only 30% of prints for theatrical exhibition (at least in the UK) were in 2D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] His suspicions were later reinforced by a substantial number of complaints about *Dredd* from those who wished to see it in 2D but were denied the opportunity.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In July 2017, IMAX announced that they would begin to focus on screening more Hollywood tentpole movies in 2D (even if there's a 3D version) and have fewer 3D screenings of movies in North America, citing that moviegoers in North America prefer 2D films over 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2024, 3D films in 4K HDR became available to home media for the first time, with the launch of the visionOS operating system offering two services to access movies in such formats: Apple TV and Disney+.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Some films were also offered in high frame rate (48fps), such as *Avatar: The Way of Water*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2025, 3D films became available to Android XR devices via the Google TV service, starting with the Samsung Galaxy XR.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Stereoscopic motion pictures can be produced through a variety of different methods.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Over the years the popularity of systems being widely employed in film theaters has waxed and waned.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Though anaglyph was sometimes used prior to 1948, during the early "Golden Era" of 3D cinematography of the 1950s the polarization system was used for every single feature-length film in the United States, and all but one short film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the 21st century, polarization 3D systems have continued to dominate the scene, though during the 1960s and 1970s some classic films which were converted to anaglyph for theaters not equipped for polarization, and were even shown in 3D on television.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the years following the mid-1980s, some films were made with short segments in anaglyph 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The following are some of the technical details and methodologies employed in some of the more notable 3D film systems that have been developed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The standard for shooting live-action films in 3D involves using two cameras mounted so that their lenses are about as far apart from each other as the average pair of human eyes, recording two separate images for both the left eye and the right eye.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In principle, two normal 2D cameras could be put side-to-side but this is problematic in many ways.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The only real option is to invest in new stereoscopic cameras.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Moreover, some cinematographic tricks that are simple with a 2D camera become impossible when filming in 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This means those otherwise cheap tricks need to be replaced by expensive CGI.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2008, *Journey to the Center of the Earth* became the first live-action feature film to be shot with the earliest Fusion Camera System released in Digital 3D and was later followed by several others.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Avatar* (2009) was shot in a 3D process that is based on how the human eye looks at an image.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It was an improvement to the existing 3D camera system.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Many 3D camera rigs still in use simply pair two cameras side by side, while newer rigs are paired with a beam splitter or both camera lenses built into one unit.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] While Digital Cinema cameras are not a requirement for 3D they are the predominant medium for most of what is photographed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Film options include IMAX 3D and Cine 160.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the 1930s and 1940s, the Fleischer Studios made several cartoons with extensive stereoscopic 3D backgrounds, including several *Popeye the Sailor*, *Betty Boop*, and *Superman* cartoons.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the early to mid-1950s, only half of the major Animation film studios operation experimented with creating traditional 3D animated short subjects.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The Walt Disney Studio produced two traditionally animated shorts in stereoscopic 3D, for cinemas.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] *Adventures in Music: Melody* (1953), and the Donald Duck cartoon *Working for Peanuts* (1953).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Cartoons only produced a single cartoon in 3D: *Lumber Jack-Rabbit* (1953) starring Bugs Bunny.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Famous Studios produced two cartoons in 3D, the Popeye cartoon *Popeye, the Ace of Space* (1953), and the Casper the Friendly Ghost cartoon *Boo Moon* (1954).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Walter Lantz Productions produced the Woody Woodpecker cartoon *Hypnotic Hick* (1953), which was distributed by Universal.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] From the late 1950s until the mid-2000s almost no animation was produced for 3D display in theaters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Although several films used 3D backgrounds.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One exception is *Starchaser: The Legend of Orin*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] CGI animated films can be rendered as stereoscopic 3D version by using two virtual cameras.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Stop-motion animated 3D films are photographed with two cameras similar to live action 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In 2004 *The Polar Express* was the first stereoscopic 3D CGI-animated feature film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The 3D version was solely released in IMAX theaters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In November 2005, Walt Disney Pictures released *Chicken Little* in Digital 3D format, being Disney's first CGI-animated film in 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The film was converted from 2D into 3D in post-production. nWave Pictures' *Fly Me to the Moon* (2008) was actually the first animated film created for 3D and released exclusively in 3D in digital theaters around the world.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] No other animation films have released solely in 3D since.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The first 3D feature by DreamWorks Animation, *Monsters vs.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Aliens*, followed in 2009 and used a new digital rendering process called InTru3D, which was developed by Intel to create more realistic animated 3D images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] InTru3D is not used to exhibit 3D films in theaters; they are shown in either RealD 3D or IMAX 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the case of 2D CGI animated films that were generated from 3D models, it is possible to return to the models to generate a 3D version.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] For all other 2D films, different techniques must be employed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] For example, for the 3D re-release of the 1993 film *The Nightmare Before Christmas*, Walt Disney Pictures scanned each original frame and manipulated them to produce left-eye and right-eye versions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Dozens of films have now been converted from 2D to 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] There are several approaches used for 2D to 3D conversion, most notably depth-based methods.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Information is unavailable as 2D does not have information for a perspective view.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Some TVs have a 3D engine to convert 2D content to 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Usually, on high frame rate content (and on some slower processors even normal frame rate) the processor is not fast enough and lag is possible.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This can lead to strange visual effects.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Anaglyph images were the earliest method of presenting theatrical 3D, and the one most commonly associated with stereoscopy by the public at large, mostly because of non-theatrical 3D media such as comic books and 3D television broadcasts, where polarization is not practical.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] They were made popular because of the ease of their production and exhibition.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The first anaglyph film was invented in 1915 by Edwin S Porter.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Though the earliest theatrical presentations were done with this system, most 3D films from the 1950s and 1980s were originally shown polarized.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In an anaglyph, the two images are superimposed in an additive light setting through two filters, one red and one cyan.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In a subtractive light setting, the two images are printed in the same complementary colors on white paper.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Glasses with colored filters in each eye separate the appropriate images by canceling the filter color out and rendering the complementary color black.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Anaglyph images are much easier to view than either parallel sighting or crossed eye stereograms, although the latter types offer bright and accurate color rendering, particularly in the red component, which is muted, or desaturated with even the best color anaglyphs.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A compensating technique, commonly known as Anachrome, uses a slightly more transparent cyan filter in the patented glasses associated with the technique.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Process reconfigures the typical anaglyph image to have less parallax.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] An alternative to the usual red and cyan filter system of anaglyph is ColorCode 3-D, a patented anaglyph system which was invented in order to present an anaglyph image in conjunction with the NTSC television standard, in which the red channel is often compromised.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] ColorCode uses the complementary colors of yellow and dark blue on-screen, and the colors of the glasses' lenses are amber and dark blue.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The polarization 3D system has been the standard for theatrical presentations since it was used for *Bwana Devil* in 1952, though early IMAX presentations were done using the eclipse system and in the 1960s and 1970s classic 3D films were sometimes converted to anaglyph for special presentations.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The polarization system has better color fidelity and less ghosting than the anaglyph system.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the post-'50s era, anaglyph has been used instead of polarization in feature presentations where only part of the film is in 3D such as in the 3D segment of *Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare* and the 3D segments of *Spy Kids 3-D: Game Over*.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Anaglyph is also used in printed materials and in 3D television broadcasts where polarization is not practical.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] 3D polarized televisions and other displays only became available from several manufacturers in 2008; these generate polarization on the receiving end.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] To present a stereoscopic motion pictures, two images are projected superimposed onto the same screen through different polarizing filters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The viewer wears low-cost glasses which also contain a pair of polarizing filters oriented differently (clockwise/counterclockwise with circular polarization or at 90 degree angles, usually 45 and 135 degrees, with linear polarization).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] As each filter passes only that light which is similarly polarized and blocks the light polarized differently, each eye sees a different image.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This is used to produce a three-dimensional effect by projecting the same scene into both eyes, but depicted from slightly different perspectives.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Since no head tracking is involved, the entire audience can view the stereoscopic images at the same time.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Circular polarization has an advantage over linear polarization, in that the viewer does not need to have their head upright and aligned with the screen for the polarization to work properly.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] With linear polarization, turning the glasses sideways causes the filters to go out of alignment with the screen filters causing the image to fade and for each eye to see the opposite frame more easily.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] For circular polarization, the polarizing effect works regardless of how the viewer's head is aligned with the screen such as tilted sideways, or even upside down.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The left eye will still only see the image intended for it, and vice versa, without fading or crosstalk.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Nonetheless, 3D cinema films are made to be viewed without head tilt, and any significant head tilt will result in incorrect parallax and prevent binocular fusion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the case of RealD a circularly polarizing liquid crystal filter which can switch polarity 144 times per second is placed in front of the projector lens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Only one projector is needed, as the left and right eye images are displayed alternately.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Sony features a new system called RealD XLS, which shows both circular polarized images simultaneously: A single 4K projector (4096×2160 resolution) displays both 2K images (2048×1080 resolution) on top of each other at the same time, a special lens attachment polarizes and projects the images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Optical attachments can be added to traditional 35 mm projectors to adapt them for projecting film in the "over-and-under" format, in which each pair of images is stacked within one frame of film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The two images are projected through different polarizers and superimposed on the screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This is a very cost-effective way to convert a theater for 3D as all that is needed are the attachments and a non-depolarizing screen surface, rather than a conversion to digital 3D projection.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Thomson Technicolor currently produces an adapter of this type.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A metallic screen is necessary for these systems as reflection from non-metallic surfaces destroys the polarization of the light.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Polarized stereoscopic pictures have been around since 1936, when Edwin H.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Land first applied it to motion pictures.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The so-called "3-D movie craze" in the years 1952 through 1955 was almost entirely offered in theaters using linear polarizing projection and glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Only a minute amount of the total 3D films shown in the period used the anaglyph color filter method.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Linear polarization was likewise used with consumer level stereo projectors.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Polarization was also used during the 3D revival of the 1980s.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In the 2000s, computer animation, competition from DVDs and other media, digital projection, and the use of sophisticated IMAX 70 mm film projectors, have created an opportunity for a new wave of polarized 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] All types of polarization will result in a darkening of the displayed image and poorer contrast compared to non-3D images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Light from lamps is normally emitted as a random collection of polarizations, while a polarization filter only passes a fraction of the light.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] As a result, the screen image is darker.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This darkening can be compensated by increasing the brightness of the projector light source.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] If the initial polarization filter is inserted between the lamp and the image generation element, the light intensity striking the image element is not any higher than normal without the polarizing filter, and overall image contrast transmitted to the screen is not affected.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In this technology, a mechanism is used to block light from each appropriate eye when the converse eye's image is projected on the screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The technology originated with the Eclipse Method, in which the projector alternates between left and right images, and opens and closes the shutters in the glasses or viewer in synchronization with the images on the screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This was the basis of the Teleview system which was used briefly in 1922.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A newer implementation of the Eclipse Method came with liquid-crystal shutter glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Glasses containing liquid crystal that will let light through in synchronization with the images on the cinema, television or computer screen, using the concept of alternate-frame sequencing.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This is the method used by nVidia, XpanD 3D, and earlier IMAX systems.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] A drawback of this method is the need for each person viewing to wear expensive, electronic glasses that must be synchronized with the display system using a wireless signal or attached wire.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The shutter-glasses are heavier than most polarized glasses, though lighter models are no heavier than some sunglasses or deluxe polarized glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] However these systems do not require a silver screen for projected images.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Liquid crystal light valves work by rotating light between two polarizing filters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Due to these internal polarizers, LCD shutter-glasses darken the display image of any LCD, plasma, or projector image source, which has the result that images appear dimmer and contrast is lower than for normal non-3D viewing.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This is not necessarily a usage problem; for some types of displays which are already very bright with poor grayish black levels, LCD shutter glasses may actually improve the image quality.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Dolby 3D uses specific wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the right eye, and different wavelengths of red, green, and blue for the left eye.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Glasses which filter out the very specific wavelengths allow the wearer to see a 3D image.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This technology eliminates the expensive silver screens required for polarized systems such as RealD, which is the most common 3D display system in theaters.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It does, however, require much more expensive glasses than the polarized systems.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The recently introduced Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system also uses this technology, though with a wider spectrum and more "teeth" to the "comb" (5 for each eye in the Omega/Panavision system).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The use of more spectral bands per eye eliminates the need to color process the image, required by the Dolby system.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Evenly dividing the visible spectrum between the eyes gives the viewer a more relaxed "feel" as the light energy and color balance is nearly 50-50.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Like the Dolby system, the Omega system can be used with white or silver screens.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] But it can be used with either film or digital projectors, unlike the Dolby filters that are only used on a digital system with a color correcting processor provided by Dolby.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The Omega/Panavision system also claims that their glasses are cheaper to manufacture than those used by Dolby.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In June 2012 the Omega 3D/Panavision 3D system was discontinued by DPVO Theatrical, who marketed it on behalf of Panavision, citing "challenging global economic and 3D market conditions".
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Although DPVO dissolved its business operations, Omega Optical continues promoting and selling 3D systems to non-theatrical markets.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Omega Optical's 3D system contains projection filters and 3D glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In addition to the passive stereoscopic 3D system, Omega Optical has produced enhanced anaglyph 3D glasses.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The Omega's red/cyan anaglyph glasses use complex metal oxide thin film coatings and high quality annealed glass optics.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In this method, glasses are not necessary to see a 3D image.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] To produce the 3D effect, the person must be positioned so that one eye sees one of the two images and the other sees the other.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Both images are projected onto a high-gain, corrugated screen that reflects light at acute angles.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] In order to see the stereoscopic image, the viewer must sit within a very narrow angle that is nearly perpendicular to the screen, limiting the size of the audience.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Lenticular was used for theatrical presentation of numerous shorts in Russia from 1940 to 1948 and in 1946 for the feature-length film Robinson Crusoe.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Though lenticular's use in theatrical presentations has been rather limited, it has been widely used for a variety of novelty items and has even been used in amateur 3D photography.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Recent use includes the Fujifilm FinePix Real 3D with an autostereoscopic display that was released in 2009.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Other examples for this technology include autostereoscopic liquid crystal displays on monitors, notebooks, TVs, mobile phones and gaming devices, such as the Nintendo 3DS.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Some viewers have complained of headaches and eyestrain after watching 3D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Motion sickness, in addition to other health concerns, are more easily induced by 3D presentations.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] One published study shows that of those who watch 3D films, nearly 55% experience varying levels of headaches, nausea and disorientation.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] Glasses designed to eliminate eyestrain by converting 3D images back into 2D have been developed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] It is believed that approximately 12% of people are unable to properly see 3D images, due to a variety of medical conditions.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] According to another experiment up to 30% of people have very weak stereoscopic vision preventing them from depth perception based on stereo disparity.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] This nullifies or greatly decreases immersion effects of digital stereo to them.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p02] The French National Research Agency (ANR) has sponsored multidisciplinary research in order to understand the effects of 3D film viewing, its grammar, and its acceptance.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Most of the cues required to provide humans with relative depth information are already present in traditional 2D films.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] In fact, only two of these depth cues are not already present in 2D films: stereopsis (or parallax) and the focus of the eyeball (accommodation).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] 3D film-making addresses accurate presentation of stereopsis but not of accommodation, and therefore is insufficient in providing a complete 3D illusion.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] However, promising results from research aimed at overcoming this shortcoming were presented at the 2010 Stereoscopic Displays and Applications conference in San Jose, U.S.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Film critic Mark Kermode argued that 3D adds "not that much" value to a film, and said that, while he liked *Avatar*, the many impressive things he saw in the film had nothing to do with 3D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Kermode has been an outspoken critic of 3D film describing the effect as a "nonsense" and recommends using two right or left lenses from the 3D glasses to cut out the "pointy, pointy 3D stereoscopic vision", although this technique still does not improve the huge brightness loss from a 3D film.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Versions of these "2-D glasses" are being marketed.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Director Christopher Nolan has criticised the notion that traditional film does not allow depth perception, saying "I think it's a misnomer to call it 3D versus 2D.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] The whole point of cinematic imagery is it's three dimensional...
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Late film critic Roger Ebert repeatedly criticized 3D film as being "too dim", sometimes distracting or even nausea-inducing, and argued that it is an expensive technology that adds nothing of value to the film-going experience (since 2-D films already provide a sufficient illusion of 3D).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] While Ebert was "not opposed to 3-D as an option", he opposed it as a replacement for traditional film, and preferred 2-D technologies such as MaxiVision48 that improve image area/resolution and frames per second.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Most 3D systems will cut down the brightness of the picture considerably – the light loss can be as high as 88%.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Some of this loss may be compensated by running the projector's bulb at higher power or using more powerful bulbs.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] The 2D brightness cinema standard is 14 foot-lamberts (48 candela per square metre), as set by the SMPTE standard 196M.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] As of 2012, there is no official standard for 3D brightness.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] According to the industry de facto standard, however, the "acceptable brightness range" goes as low as 3.5 fL (12 cd/m2) – just 25% of the standard 2D brightness.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] In September 2012, the DCI standards body issued a "recommended practice" calling for a 3D projection brightness of 7 fL (24 cd/m2), with an acceptable range of 5–9 fL (17–31 cd/m2).
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] It is not known how many theaters actually achieve such light levels with current technology.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Prototype laser projection systems have reached 14 fL (48 cd/m2) for 3D on a cinema screen.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Another major criticism is that many of the films in the 21st century to date were not filmed in 3D, but converted to 3D after filming.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Filmmakers who have criticized the quality of this process include James Cameron (whose film *Avatar* was created mostly in 3D from the ground up, with some portions of the film created in 2D, and is largely credited with the revival of 3D) and Michael Bay.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] However, Cameron has said that quality 2D to 3D conversions can be done if they take the time they need and the director is involved.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] Cameron's *Titanic* was converted into 3D in 2012, taking 60 weeks and costing $18 million.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] In contrast, computer-animated films for which the original computer models are still available can be rendered in 3D easily, as the depth information is still available and does not need to be inferred or approximated.
[src:cinematography/3-d-film-p03] This has been done with *Toy Story*, among others.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] A variety of largely proprietary gauges were devised for the numerous camera and projection systems being developed independently in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, along with various film feeding systems.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This resulted in cameras, projectors, and other equipment having to be calibrated to each gauge.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The 35 mm width, originally specified as 1+3⁄8 inches, was introduced around 1890 by William Kennedy Dickson and Thomas Edison, using film stock supplied by George Eastman.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Film 35 mm wide with four perforations per frame became accepted as the international standard gauge in 1909, and remained by far the dominant film gauge for image origination and projection until the advent of digital photography and cinematography.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The gauge has been versatile in application.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] It has been modified to include sound, redesigned to create a safer film base, formulated to capture color, has accommodated a bevy of widescreen formats, and has incorporated digital sound data into nearly all of its non-frame areas.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Eastman Kodak, Fujifilm and Agfa-Gevaert are some companies that offered 35 mm films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] As of 2015, Kodak is the last remaining manufacturer of motion picture film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The ubiquity of 35 mm movie projectors in commercial movie theaters made 35 mm the only motion picture format that could be played in almost any cinema in the world, until digital projection largely superseded it.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1880, George Eastman began to manufacture gelatin dry photographic plates in Rochester, New York.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Walker, Eastman invented a holder for a roll of picture-carrying gelatin layer-coated paper.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Hannibal Goodwin then invented a nitrocellulose film base in 1887, the first transparent, flexible film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Eastman also produced these components, and his was the first major company to mass-produce such film when, in 1889, Eastman realized that the dry-gelatino-bromide emulsion could be coated onto this clear base, eliminating the paper.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] With the advent of flexible film, Thomas Edison quickly set out on his invention, the Kinetoscope, which was first shown at the Brooklyn Institute of Arts and Sciences on May 9, 1893.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Kinetoscope was a film loop system intended for one-person viewing.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Edison, along with assistant William Kennedy Dickson, followed that up with the Kinetophone, which combined the Kinetoscope with Edison's cylinder phonograph.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Beginning in March 1892, Eastman and then, from April 1893 into 1896, New York's Blair Camera Co. supplied Edison with film stock.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Edison's aperture defined a single frame of film at four perforations high.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Around 1896, a 35 mm projector known as a "photo-rotoscope" was made by W.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Hughes in London, which advanced the film by means of a "dog" motion.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] A court judgment in March 1902 invalidated Edison's claim, allowing any producer or distributor to use the Edison 35 mm film design without license.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Filmmakers were already doing so in Britain and Europe, where Edison did not file patents.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] At the time, film stock was usually supplied unperforated and punched by the filmmaker to their standards with perforation equipment.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] A variation developed by the Lumière brothers used a single circular perforation on each side of the frame towards the middle of the horizontal axis.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] When films began to be projected, several projection devices were unsuccessful and fell into obscurity because of technical failure, lack of business acumen on the part of their promoters, or both.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Vitascope, the first projection device to use 35 mm, was technologically superior and compatible with the many motion pictures produced on 35 mm film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] When film editing was done by physically cutting the film, editing the picture could only have been done on the frame line.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] However, the sound was stored for the whole frame between each of the four sprocket holes, and so the sound editors could cut on any arbitrary set of holes, and thus get +1⁄4-frame edit resolution.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Three different digital soundtrack systems for 35 mm cinema release prints were introduced during the 1990s.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Because these soundtrack systems appear on different parts of the film, one movie can contain all of them, allowing broad distribution without regard for the sound system installed at individual theatres.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The analogue optical track technology has also changed: in the early years of the 21st century, distributors changed to using cyan dye optical soundtracks instead of applicated tracks, which use environmentally unfriendly chemicals to retain a silver (black-and-white) soundtrack.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Because traditional incandescent exciter lamps produce copious amounts of infrared light, and cyan tracks do not absorb infrared light, this change has required theaters to replace the incandescent exciter lamp with a complementary colored red LED or laser.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These LED or laser exciters are backwards-compatible with older tracks.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The film *Anything Else* (2003) was the first to be released with only cyan tracks.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] To facilitate this changeover, intermediate prints known as "high magenta" prints were distributed.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These prints used a silver plus dye soundtrack that were printed into the magenta dye layer.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The advantage gained was an optical soundtrack, with low levels of sibilant (cross-modulation) distortion, on both types of sound heads.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The success of digitally projected 3D movies in the first two decades of the 21st century led to a demand from some theater owners to be able to show these movies in 3D without incurring the high capital cost of installing digital projection equipment.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] To satisfy that demand, a number of systems had been proposed for 3D systems based on 35 mm film by Technicolor, Panavision and others.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These systems are improved versions of the "over-under" stereo 3D prints first introduced in the 1960s.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] To be attractive to exhibitors, these schemes offered 3D films that can be projected by a standard 35 mm cinema projector with minimal modification, and so they are based on the use of "over-under" film prints.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In these prints a left-right pair of 2.39:1 non-anamorphic images are substituted for the one 2.39:1 anamorphic image of a 2D "scope" print.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The frame dimensions are based on those of the Techniscope 2-perf camera format used in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] However, when used for 3D the left and right frames are pulled down together, thus the standard 4-perf pulldown is retained, minimising the need for modifications to the projector or to long-play systems.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The linear speed of film through the projector and sound playback both remain exactly the same as in normal 2D operation.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Technicolor system uses the polarisation of light to separate the left and right eye images and for this they rent to exhibitors a combination splitter-polarizer-lens assembly which can be fitted to a lens turret in the same manner as an anamorphic lens.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In contrast, the Panavision system uses a spectral comb filter system, but their combination splitter-filter-lens is physically similar to the Technicolor assembly and can be used in the same way.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] No other modifications are required to the projector for either system, though for the Technicolor system a silver screen is necessary, as it would be with polarised-light digital 3D.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Thus a programme can readily include both 2D and 3D segments with only the lens needing to be changed between them.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In June 2012, Panavision 3D systems for both 35 mm film and digital projection were withdrawn from the market by DVPO theatrical (who marketed these system on behalf of Panavision) citing "challenging global economic and 3D market conditions".
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In the transition period centered around 2010–2015, the rapid conversion of the cinema exhibition industry to digital projection saw 35 mm film projectors removed from most of the projection rooms as they were replaced by digital projectors.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] By the mid-2010s, most of the theaters across the world had been converted to digital projection, although a small percentage (under 10% overall) continued running 35 mm projectors, mostly indie theaters or those in more economically challenged regions.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] However, it continued as a niche market for enthusiasts and format lovers.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In the 2020s, 35 mm has seen some resurgence in usage.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The resurgence comes from those who find 35 mm to be more visually pleasing and evoke nostalgic feelings, as well as a desire from millennial and Generation Z filmmakers and photographers to preserve the art.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Several films such as *Marty Supreme* and *Anora* have been produced using 35 mm film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In an effort to rebuild business lost during the COVID-19 pandemic, some theaters have used special event screenings of films with 35 mm film projectors to attract customers.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Most of these screenings occur in large metropolitan areas.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Originally, film was a strip of cellulose nitrate coated with black-and-white photographic emulsion.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Griffith, color tinted or toned portions of their movies for dramatic impact, and by 1920, 80 to 90 percent of all films were tinted.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The first successful natural color process was Britain's Kinemacolor (1909–1915), a two-color additive process that used a rotating disk with red and green filters in front of the camera lens and the projector lens.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] But any process that photographed and projected the colors sequentially was subject to color "fringing" around moving objects, and a general color flickering.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1916, William Van Doren Kelley began developing Prizma, the first commercially viable American color process using 35 mm film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Initially, like Kinemacolor, it photographed the color elements one after the other and projected the results by additive synthesis.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Ultimately, Prizma was refined to bipack photography, with two strips of film, one treated to be sensitive to red and the other not, running through the camera face to face.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This system of two-color bipack photography and two-sided prints was the basis for many later color processes, such as Multicolor, Brewster Color and Cinecolor.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Although it had been available previously, color in Hollywood feature films first became truly practical from the studios' commercial perspective with the advent of Technicolor, whose main advantage was quality prints in less time than its competitors.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In its earliest incarnations, Technicolor was another two-color system that could reproduce a range of reds, muted bluish greens, pinks, browns, tans and grays, but not real blues or yellows.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] *The Toll of the Sea*, released in 1922, was the first film printed in their subtractive color system.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Technicolor's camera photographed each pair of color-filtered frames simultaneously on one strip of black-and-white film by means of a beam splitter prism behind the camera lens.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Two prints on half-thickness stock were made from the negative, one from only the red-filtered frames, the other from the green-filtered frames.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] After development, the silver images on the prints were chemically toned to convert them into images of the approximately complementary colors.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The two strips were then cemented together back to back, forming a single strip similar to duplitized film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1928, Technicolor started making their prints by the imbibition process, which was mechanical rather than photographic and allowed the color components to be combined on the same side of the film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Using two matrix films bearing hardened gelatin relief images, thicker where the image was darker, aniline color dyes were transferred into the gelatin coating on a third, blank strip of film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Technicolor re-emerged as a three-color process for cartoons in 1932 and live action in 1934.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Using a different arrangement of a beam-splitter cube and color filters behind the lens, the camera simultaneously exposed three individual strips of black-and-white film, each one recording one-third of the spectrum, which allowed virtually the entire spectrum of colors to be reproduced.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] A printing matrix with a hardened gelatin relief image was made from each negative, and the three matrices transferred color dyes into a blank film to create the print.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Two-color processes, however, were far from extinct.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Gundelfinger revived the Multicolor process under the company name Cinecolor.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Cinecolor saw considerable use in animation and low-budget pictures, mainly because it cost much less than three-color Technicolor.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] If color design was carefully managed, the lack of colors such as true green could pass unnoticed.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Although Cinecolor used the same duplitized stock as Prizma and Multicolor, it had the advantage that its printing and processing methods yielded larger quantities of finished film in less time.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1950, Kodak announced the first Eastman color 35 mm negative film (along with a complementary positive film) that could record all three primary colors on the same strip of film.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] An improved version in 1952 was quickly adopted by Hollywood, making the use of three-strip Technicolor cameras and bipack cameras (used in two-color systems such as Cinecolor) obsolete in color cinematography.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This "monopack" structure is made up of three separate emulsion layers, one sensitive to red light, one to green and one to blue.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Although Eastman Kodak had first introduced acetate-based film, it was far too brittle and prone to shrinkage, so the dangerously flammable nitrate-based cellulose films were generally used for motion picture camera and print films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1949 Kodak began replacing all nitrocellulose (nitrate-based) films with the safer, more robust cellulose triacetate-based "Safety" films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1950 the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences awarded Kodak with a Scientific and Technical Academy Award (Oscar) for the safer triacetate stock.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] By 1952, all camera and projector films were triacetate-based.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Most if not all film prints today are made from synthetic polyester safety base (which started replacing Triacetate film for prints in the early 1990s).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The downside of polyester film is that it is extremely strong, and, in case of a fault, will stretch and not break–potentially causing damage to the projector and ruining a fairly large stretch of film: 2–3 ft or approximately 2 seconds.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Also, polyester film will melt if exposed to the projector lamp for too long.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Polyester films are not compatible with solvent-based assembly processes.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Besides black & white and color negative films, there are black & white and color reversal films, which when developed create a positive ("natural") image that is projectable.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] There are also films sensitive to non-visible wavelengths of light, such as infrared.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In the conventional motion picture format, frames are four perforations tall, with an aspect ratio of 1.375:1, 22 by 16 mm (0.866 by 0.630 in).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This is a derivation of the aspect ratio and frame size designated by Thomas Edison (24.89 by 18.67 millimetres or 0.980 by 0.735 inches) at the dawn of motion pictures, which was an aspect ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The first sound features were released in 1926–27, and while Warner Bros. was using synchronized phonograph discs (sound-on-disc), Fox placed the soundtrack in an optical record directly on the film (sound-on-film) on a strip between the sprocket holes and the image frame.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] "Sound-on-film" was soon adopted by the other Hollywood studios, resulting in an almost square image ratio of 0.860 in by 0.820 in.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] By 1929, most movie studios had revamped this format using their own house aperture plate size to try to recreate the older screen ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Furthermore, every theater chain had their own house aperture plate size in which the picture was projected.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These sizes often did not match up even between theaters and studios owned by the same company, and therefore, uneven projection practices occurred.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In November 1929, the Society of Motion Picture Engineers set a standard aperture ratio of 0.800 in by 0.600 in.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Known as the "1930 standard", studios which followed the suggested practice of marking their camera viewfinders for this ratio were: Paramount-Famous-Lasky, Metro-Goldwyn Mayer, United Artists, Pathe, Universal, RKO, Tiffany-Stahl, Mack Sennett, Darmour, and Educational.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Fox Studio markings were the same width but allowed .04 in more height.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1932, in refining this ratio, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences expanded upon this 1930 standard.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The camera aperture became 22 by 16 mm (0.87 by 0.63 in), and the projected image would use an aperture plate size of 0.825 by 0.600 in (21.0 by 15.2 mm), yielding an aspect ratio of 1.375:1.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This became known as the "Academy" ratio.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Since the 1950s the aspect ratio of some theatrically released motion picture films has been 1.85:1 (1.66:1 in Europe) or 2.35:1 (2.40:1 after 1970).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The image area for "TV transmission" is slightly smaller than the full "Academy" ratio at 21 by 16 mm (0.83 by 0.63 in), an aspect ratio of 1.33:1.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Hence when the "Academy" ratio is referred to as having an aspect ratio of 1.33:1, it is done so mistakenly.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The commonly used anamorphic format uses a similar four-perf frame, but an anamorphic lens is used on the camera and projector to produce a wider image, today with an aspect ratio of about 2.39:1 (more commonly referred to as 2.40:1).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The ratio was formerly 2.35:1—and is still often mistakenly referred to as such—until an SMPTE revision of projection standards in 1970.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The image, as recorded on the negative and print, is horizontally compressed (squeezed) by a factor of 2.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The unexpected success of the Cinerama widescreen process in 1952 led to a boom in film format innovations to compete with the growing audiences of television and the dwindling audiences in movie theaters.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These processes could give theatergoers an experience that television could not at that time—color, stereophonic sound and panoramic vision.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Before the end of the year, 20th Century Fox had narrowly "won" a race to obtain an anamorphic optical system invented by Henri Chrétien, and soon began promoting the Cinemascope technology as early as the production phase.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Paramount Pictures began this trend with their aspect ratio of 1.66:1, first used in *Shane*, which was originally shot for Academy ratio.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] It was Universal Studios, however, with their May release of *Thunder Bay* that introduced the now standard 1.85:1 format to American audiences and brought attention to the industry the capability and low cost of equipping theaters for this transition.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Other studios followed suit with aspect ratios of 1.75:1 up to 2:1.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] For a time, these various ratios were used by different studios in different productions, but by 1956, the aspect ratio of 1.85:1 became the "standard" US format.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These *flat* films are photographed with the full Academy frame, but are matted (most often with a mask in the theater projector, not in the camera) to obtain the "wide" aspect ratio.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The standard, in some European countries, became 1.66:1 instead of 1.85:1, although some productions with pre-determined American distributors composed for the latter to appeal to US markets.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In September 1953, 20th Century Fox debuted CinemaScope with their production of *The Robe* to great success.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] CinemaScope became the first marketable usage of an anamorphic widescreen process and became the basis for a host of "formats", usually suffixed with *-scope,* that were otherwise identical in specification, although sometimes inferior in optical quality.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The 1950s and 1960s saw many other novel processes using 35 mm, such as VistaVision, SuperScope, and Technirama, most of which ultimately became obsolete.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] VistaVision, however, would be revived decades later by Lucasfilm and other studios for special effects work, while a SuperScope variant became the predecessor to the modern Super 35 format that is popular today.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The concept behind Super 35 originated with the Tushinsky Brothers' SuperScope format, particularly the SuperScope 235 specification from 1956.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1982, Joe Dunton revived the format for *Dance Craze*, and Technicolor soon marketed it under the name "Super Techniscope" before the industry settled on the name Super 35.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The cropped frame is then converted at the intermediate stage to a 4-perf anamorphically squeezed print compatible with the anamorphic projection standard.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This allows an "anamorphic" frame to be captured with non-anamorphic lenses, which are much more common.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Until the year 2000, once the film was photographed in Super 35, an optical printer was used to anamorphose (squeeze) the image.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This optical step reduced the overall quality of the image and made Super 35 a controversial subject among cinematographers, many who preferred the higher image quality and frame negative area of anamorphic photography (especially with regard to granularity).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The non-anamorphic widescreen ratios (most commonly 1.85:1) used in modern feature films makes inefficient use of the available image area on 35 mm film using the standard 4-perf pulldown; the height of a 1.85:1 frame occupying only 65% of the distance between the frames.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] It is clear, therefore, that a change to a 3-perf pulldown would allow for a 25% reduction in film consumption whilst still accommodating the full 1.85:1 frame.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Ever since the introduction of these widescreen formats in the 1950s various film directors and cinematographers have argued in favour of the industry making such a change.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Canadian cinematographer Miklos Lente invented and patented a three-perforation pull down system which he called "Trilent 35" in 1975 though he was unable to persuade the industry to adopt it.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The idea was later taken up by the Swedish film-maker Rune Ericson who was a strong advocate for the 3-perf system.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Ericson shot his 51st feature *Pirates of the Lake* in 1986 using two Panaflex cameras modified to 3-perf pulldown and suggested that the industry could change over completely over the course of ten-years.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] However, the movie industry did not make the change mainly because it would have required the modification of the thousands of existing 35 mm projectors in movie theaters all over the world.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Whilst it would have been possible to shoot in 3-perf and then convert to standard 4-perf for release prints the extra complications this would cause and the additional optical printing stage required made this an unattractive option at the time for most film makers.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] However, in television production, where compatibility with an installed base of 35 mm film projectors is unnecessary, the 3-perf format is sometimes used, giving—if used with Super 35—the 16:9 ratio used by HDTV and reducing film usage by 25 percent.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Because of 3-perf's incompatibility with standard 4-perf equipment, it can utilize the whole negative area between the perforations (Super 35) without worrying about compatibility with existing equipment; the Super 35 image area includes what would be the soundtrack area in a standard print.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] All 3-perf negatives require optical or digital conversion to standard 4-perf if a film print is desired, though 3-perf can easily be transferred to video with little to no difficulty by modern telecine or film scanners.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] With digital intermediate now a standard process for feature film post-production, 3-perf is becoming increasingly popular for feature film productions which would otherwise be averse to an optical conversion stage.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The VistaVision motion picture format was created in 1954 by Paramount Pictures to create a finer-grained negative and print for flat widescreen films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Similar to still photography, the format uses a camera running 35 mm film horizontally instead of vertically through the camera, with frames that are eight perforations long, resulting in a wider aspect ratio of 1.5:1 and greater detail, as more of the negative area is used per frame.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This format is unprojectable in standard theaters and requires an optical step to reduce the image into the standard 4-perf vertical 35 mm frame.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Its usage has again declined since the dominance of computer-based visual effects, although it still sees limited utilization.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Film perforations were originally round holes cut into the side of the film, but as these perforations were subject to wear and deformation, the shape was changed to what is now called the Bell & Howell (BH) perforation, which has straight top and bottom edges and outward curving sides.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The BH perforation's dimensions are 0.110 inches (2.8 mm) from the middle of the side curve to opposite top corner by 0.073 inches (1.9 mm) in height.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The BH1866 perforation, or BH perforation with a pitch of 0.1866 inches (4.74 mm), is the modern standard for negative and internegative films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Because BH has sharp corners, the repeated use of the film through intermittent movement projectors creates strain that can easily tear the perforations.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Furthermore, they tended to shrink as the print slowly decayed.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Therefore, larger perforations with a rectangular base and rounded corners were introduced by Kodak in 1924 to improve steadiness, registration, durability, and longevity.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The increased height also means that the image registration was considerably less accurate than BH perfs, which remains the standard for negatives.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The KS1870 perforation, or KS perforation with a pitch of 0.1870 inches (4.75 mm), is the modern standard for release prints.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These two perforations have remained by far the most commonly used ones.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] BH perforations are also known as *N* (negative) and KS as *P* (positive).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Bell & Howell perf remains the standard for camera negative films because of its perforation dimensions in comparison to most printers, thus it can keep a steady image compared to other perforations.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The Dubray–Howell (DH) perforation was first proposed in 1932 to replace the two perfs with a single hybrid.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The proposed standard was, like KS, rectangular with rounded corners and a width of 0.1100 inches (2.79 mm), and, like BH, was 0.073 inches (1.9 mm) tall.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] This gave it longer projection life but also improved registration.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] One of its primary applications was usage in Technicolor's dye imbibition printing (dye transfer).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The DH perf never had broad uptake, and Kodak's introduction of monopack Eastmancolor film in the 1950s reduced the demand for dye transfer, although the DH perforation persists in special application intermediate films.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] In 1953, the introduction of CinemaScope by Fox Studios required the creation of a different shape of perforation which was nearly square and smaller to provide space for four magnetic sound stripes for stereophonic and surround sound.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] These perforations are commonly referred to as CinemaScope (CS) or "Fox hole" perfs.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Their dimensions are 0.0780 inches (1.98 mm) in width by 0.0730 inches (1.85 mm) in height.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Due to the size difference, CS perfed film cannot be run through a projector with standard KS sprocket teeth, but KS prints *can* be run on sprockets with CS teeth.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Shrunken film with KS prints that would normally be damaged in a projector with KS sprockets may sometimes be run far more gently through a projector with CS sprockets because of the smaller size of the teeth.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Magnetic striped 35 mm film became obsolete in the 1980s after the advent of Dolby Stereo, as a result film with CS perfs is no longer manufactured.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] During continuous contact printing, the raw stock and the negative are placed next to one another around the sprocket wheel of the printer.
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] The negative, which is the closer of the two to the sprocket wheel (thus creating a slightly shorter path), must have a marginally shorter pitch between perforations (0.1866 in pitch); the raw stock has a long pitch (0.1870 in).
[src:cinematography/35mm-movie-film] Technical specifications for 35 mm film are standardized by SMPTE.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] A **360-degree video** (or **360° video**), also known as **surround video**, or **immersive video** or **spherical video**, is a video recording where a view in all directions is recorded at the same time, shot using an omnidirectional camera or a collection of cameras.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] The term *360x180* can be used to indicate 360° of azimuth and 180° from nadir to zenith.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] During playback on normal flat display the viewer has control of the viewing direction like an immersive panorama.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] It can also be played on a display or projectors arranged in a sphere or some part of a sphere.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] 360-degree video is typically recorded using either a special rig of multiple cameras, or using a dedicated camera that contains multiple camera lenses embedded into the device, and recording overlapping angles simultaneously.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Specialized omnidirectional cameras and rigs have been developed for the purpose of recording 360-degree video, including rigs such as GoPro's Omni and Odyssey (which consist of multiple action cameras installed within a frame), and contained cameras like the Nokia OZO.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] There have also been handheld dual-lens cameras such as the Ricoh Theta S, Samsung Gear 360, Garmin VIRB 360, and the Kogeto Dot 360—a panoramic camera lens accessory for smartphone cameras.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] This separate footage is stitched into one spherical video piece, and the color and contrast of each shot is calibrated to be consistent with the others.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] This process is done either by the camera itself, or using specialized software that can analyze common visuals and audio to synchronize and link the different camera feeds together.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Generally, the only area that cannot be viewed is the view toward the camera support.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] 360-degree video is typically formatted in an equirectangular projection and is either monoscopic, with one image directed to both eyes, or stereoscopic, viewed as two distinct images directed individually to each eye for a 3D effect.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Due to this projection and stitching, equirectangular video exhibits a lower quality in the middle of the image than at the top and bottom.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Spherical videos are frequently in curvilinear perspective with a fisheye effect.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] The heavy barrel distortion often requires rectilinear correction before applications in detection, tracking or navigation.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Some storytellers refer to 360-degree video that uses professional cinematic production techniques such as lighting design, sound design, scenic design, and blocking techniques as cinematic virtual reality (or cine-VR for short).
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] 360-degree videos are typically viewed via personal computers, mobile devices such as smartphones, or dedicated head-mounted displays.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Users can pan around the video by clicking and dragging.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] On smartphones, internal sensors such as the gyroscope can also be used to pan the video based on the orientation of the device.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Taking advantage of this behavior, stereoscope-style enclosures for smartphones (such as Google Cardboard viewers and the Samsung Gear VR) can be used to view 360-degree videos in an immersive format similar to virtual reality.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] The phone display is viewed through lenses contained within the enclosure, as opposed to virtual reality headsets that contain their own dedicated displays.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] In March 2015, YouTube launched support for publishing and viewing 360-degree videos, with playback on its website and its Android mobile apps.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Parent company Google also announced that it would collaborate with camera manufacturers to make it easier for creators to upload 360-degree content recorded with their products to YouTube.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Facebook (parent company of VR headset maker Oculus VR) followed suit by adding 360-degree video support in September 2015, and subsequently unveiled reference designs for its own 360-degree camera systems known as Facebook Surround 360.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Facebook announced in March 2017 that more than 1 million 360-degree videos had been uploaded to Facebook to date.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] Vimeo also launched 360-degree video support in March 2017.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] The use of the term "virtual reality" to describe 360-degree video has been disputed, as VR typically refers to interactive experiences wherein the viewer's motions can be tracked to allow real-time interactions within a virtual environment, with orientation and position tracking.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] In 360-degree video, the locations of viewers are fixed, viewers are limited to the angles captured by the cameras, and cannot interact with the environment.
[src:cinematography/360-degree-video] The non-dynamic nature of video also means that rendering techniques cannot be used to reduce the risk of motion sickness.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Each frame is five perforations tall (i.e., 23.8125 mm or 15/16 inches tall), with an image aspect ratio of 2.2:1.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The use of anamorphic Ultra Panavision 70 lenses squeezes an ultra-wide 2.76:1 aspect ratio horizontally into that 2.2:1 imaging area.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] To this day, Ultra Panavision 70 produces the second widest picture size; surpassed only by Polyvision, which was only used for 1927's *Napoléon*.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] With regard to exhibition, 70 mm film was always considered a specialty format reserved for epics and spectacle films shot on 65 mm and blockbuster films that were released both in 35 mm and as 70 mm blow-ups.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] While few venues were equipped to screen this special format, at the height of its popularity most major markets and cities had a theater that could screen it.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Some venues continue to screen 70 mm to this day or have even had 70 mm projectors permanently or temporarily installed for more recent 70 mm releases.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Films formatted with a width of 70 mm have existed since the early days of the motion picture industry.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The first 70 mm format film was most likely footage of the Henley Regatta, which was projected in 1896 and 1897, but may have been filmed as early as 1894.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] It required a specially built projector built by Herman Casler in Canastota, New York and had a ratio similar to full frame, with an aperture of 2.75 inches (70 mm) by 2 inches (51 mm).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] There were also several film formats of various sizes from 50 to 68 mm which were developed from 1884 onwards, including Cinéorama (not to be confused with the entirely distinct "Cinerama" format), started in 1900 by Raoul Grimoin-Sanson.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] In 1914 the Italian Filoteo Alberini invented a panoramic film system utilising a 70 mm wide film called Panoramica.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] In 1928, William Fox of the Fox Film Corporation, in personal collaboration with Theodore Case as the Fox-Case Corporation, began working on a wide film format using 70 mm film which they named Grandeur.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Cameras were ordered by Fox-Case from Mitchell Camera Corp, with the first 70 mm production cameras, designated as the Mitchell Model FC camera, delivered to Fox-Case in May 1929.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This was one of a number of wide-film processes developed by some of the major film studios at about that time.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] However, due to the financial strains of the Great Depression, along with strong resistance from movie theater owners, who were in the process of equipping their theaters for sound, none of these systems became commercially successful.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Producer Mike Todd had been one of the founders of Cinerama, a wide-screen movie process that was launched in 1952.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Cinerama employed three 35 mm film projectors running in synchronism to project a wide (2.6:1) image onto a deeply curved screen.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Although the results were impressive, the system was expensive, cumbersome and had some serious shortcomings due to the need to match up three separate projected images.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Todd left the company to develop a system of his own which, he hoped, would be as impressive as Cinerama, yet be simpler and cheaper and avoid the problems associated with three-strip projection; in his own words, he wanted "Cinerama out of one hole".
[src:cinematography/65-mm] In collaboration with the American Optical Company, Todd developed a system which was to be called "Todd-AO".
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This uses a single 70 mm wide film and was introduced with the film *Oklahoma!* in October 1955.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The 70 mm film is perforated at the same pitch (0.187 inch, 4.75 mm) as standard 35 mm film.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] With a five-perforation pull-down, the Todd-AO system provides a frame dimension of 1.912 inch (48.56 mm) by 0.87 inch (22.09 mm) giving an aspect ratio of 2.2:1.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The Todd-AO format was originally intended to use a deeply curved Cinerama-type screen but this failed to survive beyond the first few films.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] However, in the 1960s and 70s, such films as *The Sound of Music* and *Patton* (which had been filmed in a process known as Dimension 150) were shown in some Cinerama theaters, which allowed for deeply curved screens.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Todd-AO adopted a similar multi-channel magnetic sound system to the one developed for Cinemascope two years earlier, recorded on "stripes" of magnetic oxide deposited on the film.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] However, Todd-AO has six channels instead of the four of Cinemascope and due to the wider surround stripe and faster film speed provides superior audio quality.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Five of these six channels are fed to five speakers spaced behind the screen, and the sixth is fed to surround speakers around the walls of the auditorium.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Panavision developed their own 65/70 mm system that was technically compatible and virtually identical to Todd-AO.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Monikered as Super Panavision 70, it used spherical lenses and the same 2.2:1 aspect ratio at 24 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Panavision also had another 65 mm system, Ultra Panavision 70, which sprang from the MGM Camera 65 system they helped develop for MGM that was used to film *Raintree County* and *Ben-Hur*.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Both Ultra Panavision 70 and MGM Camera 65 employed an anamorphic lens with a 1.25× squeeze on a 65 mm negative (as opposed to 35 mm CinemaScope which used a 2× compression, or 8-perf, horizontally filmed 35 mm Technirama which used a 1.5× compression).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] When projected on a 70 mm print, a 1.25× anamorphic projection lens was used to decompress the image to an aspect ratio of 2.76:1, one of the widest ever used in commercial cinema.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Due to the high cost of 70 mm film and the expensive projection system and screen required to use the stock, distribution for films using the stock was limited, although this did not always hurt profits.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Most 70 mm films were also released on 35 mm film for a wider distribution after the initial debut of the film.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] *South Pacific* (1958), *Lawrence of Arabia* (1962), *My Fair Lady* (1964), and *The Sound of Music* (1965) are well-known films widely shown in 70 mm format with a general release in 35 mm format.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] 70 mm film received a brief resurgence in the 1980s when it became popular to make "blow-up" prints of 35 mm titles.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] It had another resurgence in the mid-2010s with the release of *The Master* (2012), *The Hateful Eight* (2015) and *Dunkirk* (2017), with a small number of venues getting temporary or permanent 70 mm film projectors in order to be able to screen these titles.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Quentin Tarantino, in particular, led a successful campaign to have the equipment required to show *The Hateful Eight* in Ultra Panavision installed in 100 cinemas worldwide.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The 35 mm to 70 mm "blow-up" process produces 70 mm release prints from 35 mm negatives, so that films shot on the smaller format could benefit from 70 mm image and sound quality.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This process began in the 1960s with titles like *The Cardinal* (1963) and continues up until the present day, with the height of its popularity being in the 1980s.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] If a 70 mm film was shown in a Cinerama theatre, the Cinerama sound system was used.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This layout came to be known as "5.1" (the "point one" is the low-frequency enhancement channel) and was subsequently adopted for digital sound systems used with 35 mm.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] In the 1980s the use of these "blow-ups" increased with large numbers of 70 mm prints being made of some blockbusters of the period such as the 125 70 mm prints made of *The Empire Strikes Back* (1980).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] However the early 1990s saw the advent of digital sound systems (Dolby Digital, DTS and SDDS) for 35 mm prints which meant that 35 mm could finally match 70 mm for sound quality but at a far lower cost.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Coupled with the rise of the multiplex cinema, which meant that audiences were increasingly seeing films on relatively small screens rather than the giant screens of the old "Picture Palaces", this meant that the expensive 70 mm format went out of favour again.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The DTS digital sound-on-disc system was adapted for use with 70 mm film, thus saving the significant costs of magnetic striping, but this has not been enough to stop the decline, and 70 mm prints were rarely made.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Among some of the more recent 70 mm blow-up titles are Paul Thomas Anderson's *Inherent Vice* (2014), *Phantom Thread* (2017) and *Licorice Pizza* (2021), Patty Jenkins's *Wonder Woman* (2017), Steven Spielberg's *Ready Player One* (2018) and Brady Corbet's *The Brutalist* (2024).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] From 1970, the usage of 65 mm negative film drastically reduced, although the Soviet Union (who used 70 mm stock) continued to use it frequently until the end of the 1980s.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This was in part due to the high cost of 65 mm raw stock and processing.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Some of the few films since 1990 shot entirely on 65 mm stock are Kenneth Branagh's *Hamlet* (1996), Ron Fricke's *Baraka* (1992) and its sequel, *Samsara* (2011) and Quentin Tarantino's *The Hateful Eight* (2015).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Some titles used a mixture of 5-perf and 15-perf (IMAX) 65 mm stock, including Christopher Nolan's films *Dunkirk* (2017), *Tenet* (2020) and *Oppenheimer* (2023), and Ryan Coogler's *Sinners* (2025).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Since the 2010s, most movie theaters have converted to digital projection systems, resulting in the removal of both 35 mm (the previous industry standard) projectors and 70 mm projectors.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] However some venues and organizations remain committed to screening 70 mm film, seeing the special format as something that can set them apart and be an audience draw in an industry where most movies are screened digitally.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] An anamorphic squeeze combined with 65 mm film allowed for extremely wide aspect ratios to be used while still preserving quality.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This was used in the 1957 film *Raintree County* and to incredible success in the 1959 film *Ben-Hur* and the 2015 film *The Hateful Eight*, both of which were filmed with the Ultra Panavision 70/MGM Camera 65 process at an aspect ratio of 2.76:1.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] It required the use of a 1.25× anamorphic lens to compress the image horizontally, and a corresponding lens on the projector to uncompress it.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Limited use of 65 mm film was revived in the late 1970s for some of the visual effects sequences in films like *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, mainly because the larger negative did a better job than 35 mm negative of minimizing visible film grain during optical compositing.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] 65 mm was the primary film format used at VFX pioneer Douglas Trumbull's facility EEG (Entertainment Effects Group), which later became Boss Film Studios, run by ex-Industrial Light & Magic (ILM) supervisor Richard Edlund.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Since the 1990s, a handful of films (such as *Spider-Man 2*) have used 65mm for this purpose, but the usage of digital intermediate for compositing has largely negated these issues.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Digital intermediate offers other benefits such as lower cost and a greater range of available lenses and accessories to ensure a consistent look to the footage.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] A horizontal variant of 70 mm, with an even bigger picture area, is used for the high-performance IMAX format which uses a frame that is 15 perforations wide on 70 mm film.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The Dynavision and Astrovision systems each use slightly less film per frame and vertical pulldown to save print costs while being able to project onto an IMAX screen.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Both were rare, with Astrovision largely used in Japanese planetariums.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] IMAX introduced a digital projection system in the late 2000s and most IMAX venues have migrated to a digital setup.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The first commercial introduction of 70 mm single projector 3D was the 1967 release of *Con la muerte a la espalda*, a Spanish/French/Italian co-production which used a process called Hi-Fi Stereo 70, itself based on a simplified, earlier developed Soviet process called Stereo-70.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] This process captured two anamorphic images, one for each eye, side by side on 65 mm film.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] A special lens on a 70 mm projector added polarization and merged the two images on the screen.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The 1971 re-release of Warner Bros.' *House of Wax* used the side-by-side StereoVision format and was distributed in both anamorphically squeezed 35 mm and deluxe non-anamorphic 70 mm form.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The system was developed by Allan Silliphant and Chris Condon of StereoVision International Inc., which handled all technical and marketing aspects on a five-year special-royalty basis with Warner Bros.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The big screen 3D image was both bright and clear, with all the former sync and brightness problems of traditional dual 35 mm 3D eliminated.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Still, it took many years more before IMAX began to test the water for big-screen 3D, and sold the concept to Hollywood executives.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Hollywood has released films shot on 35 mm as IMAX blow-up versions.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Many 3D films were shown in the 70 mm IMAX format.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] *The Polar Express* in IMAX 3D 70 mm earned 14 times as much, per screen, as the simultaneous 2D 35 mm release of that film in the fall of 2004.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Omnivision started in Sarasota, Florida.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Theatres were designed to compete with Omnimax but with much lower startup and operating costs.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Most theatres were built in fabric domed structures designed by Seaman Corporation.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] The last known OmniVision theatres to exist in USA are The Alaska Experience Theatre in Anchorage, Alaska, built in 1981 (closed in 2007, reopened in 2008), and the Hawaii Experience Theatre in Lahaina, Hawaii (closed in 2004).
[src:cinematography/65-mm] Rainbow's End (theme park) in NZ had the only remaining permanent Cinema 180 attraction until May 2015 when it was demolished.
[src:cinematography/65-mm] One of the few producers of 70 mm films for Cinema 180 was the German company Cinevision (today AKPservices GmbH, Paderborn).
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] There are also two other varieties of Super 8 – Single 8 mm and Straight-8 – that require different cameras but produce a final film with the same dimensions.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The standard 8 mm (also known as regular 8 or double 8) film format was developed by the Eastman Kodak company during the Great Depression and released to the market in 1932 to create a home movie format that was less expensive than 16 mm.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Double 8 spools actually contain a 16 mm film with twice as many perforations along each edge as normal 16 mm film; on its first pass through the camera, the film is exposed only along half of its width.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] When the first pass is complete, the operator opens the camera and flips and swaps the spools (the design of the spool hole ensures that the operator does this properly) and the same film is subsequently exposed along its other edge, the edge left unexposed on the first pass.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] After the film is developed, the processor splits it down the middle, resulting in two lengths of 8 mm film, each with a single row of perforations along one edge.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Each frame is half the width and half the height of a 16 mm frame, so there are four times the number of frames in a given film area, which is what makes it cost less.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Because of the two passes of the film, the format was sometimes called *Double 8*.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The frame size of regular 8 mm is 4.8 mm × 3.5 mm, and 1 meter of film contains 264 pictures.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Normally, Double 8 is filmed at 16 or 18 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Common length film spools allowed filming of about 3 to 4+1⁄2 minutes at 12, 15, 16, and 18 frames per second.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Kodak ceased sales of standard 8 mm film under its own brand in the early 1990s but continued to manufacture the film, which was sold via independent film stores.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Black-and-white 8 mm film is still manufactured in the Czech Republic, and several companies buy bulk quantities of 16 mm film to make regular 8 mm by re-perforating the stock, cutting it into 25 foot (7.6 m) lengths, and collecting it into special standard 8 mm spools, which they then sell.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Re-perforation requires special equipment.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Some specialists also produce Super 8 mm film from existing 16 mm or even 35 mm film stock.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] When Eastman Kodak first conceived the 8 mm format, no provision was made for the addition of a sound track.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Nevertheless, in the 1960s, projectors appeared on the market that were capable of recording and replaying sound from a magnetic stripe applied to the film after it had been processed.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The only part of the film wide enough to accept such a magnetic stripe was the area between the edge and the perforations.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] A much narrower stripe was sometimes added to the opposite edge so that the film piled up evenly on the spool, but was never used for sound.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The sound to picture separation was the same dimensionally as 16 mm film, and as that format is 28 frames, that meant that the Double-8 system was 56 frames.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The proximity of the sound stripe to the perforations caused some problems in keeping the film in close contact with the sound head.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] A few sound prints appeared for use in Double 8 projectors.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] In 1965, Super-8 film was released and was quickly adopted by many amateur film-makers.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] It featured a better quality image and was easier to use mainly due to a cartridge-loading system that did not require reloading and rethreading halfway through.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] To easily differentiate Super 8 film from Standard 8, projector spools for the former had larger spindle holes.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Therefore, it was not possible to mount a Super 8 spool on a Standard 8 projector, and vice versa.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The Super 8 format was designed from the start to accommodate a sound track (one of the few film formats to do so).
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] This track would occupy the area between the edge of the film and the image area.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] As in the double 8 system, a second stripe was sometimes added between the edge and the perforations.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The image to sound distance was much shorter for the Super 8 system at just 18 frames.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] At first, the magnetic stripe had to be applied after the film was processed and recorded on a suitable projector.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] In the 1970s, cameras appeared which were able to record live sound directly onto pre-striped film.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] This film was loaded into oversize cartridges that provided access for the camera's sound recording head.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The camera would also accept non sound cartridges, but silent cameras could not accept sound cartridges.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] One major advantage of the Super 8 system was that as the camera pressure plate was a part of the cartridge, it could be moulded to the profile of the stripe(s) on the film.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Projectors also appeared on the market which took advantage of the balance stripe next to the perforations by recording and replaying stereo sound.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Projectors appeared in the late 1970s that featured the ability to play films with an optical soundtrack.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The image-sound separation for the optical format was 22 frames.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] These were never popular in the English speaking world and are consequently very rare in those countries, but they did enjoy some popularity in the Far East and Europe mainly because optical prints were cheaper.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Sound prints in Super 8 were plentiful and considering that they were very expensive by modern-day standards, sold in appreciable quantities.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] A two-reel print (running approximately 17 minutes) cost around $50 with feature films costing at least $150-plus.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] A few prints were also released with stereo sound.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] In Europe, optical prints were also popular and were appreciated for their often superior sound quality.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] In theory, magnetic prints should have been superior, but Super 8 magnetic prints were often poorly recorded after the picture was processed, due to high-speed, mass production techniques.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] An optical track, on the other hand, could be printed at the same time as the image and in equivalent quality.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Another version of Super 8 film, Single-8, was produced by Fuji in Japan.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Introduced in 1965 as an alternative to the Kodak Super 8 format, it had the same final film dimensions but with a different cassette.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Unlike the co-axial design of Super 8, the Single 8 cartridge featured one spool above the other.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Single 8's film format being identical to Super 8 means that everything written above regarding projectors for Super 8 applies equally to Single 8.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Cameras also appeared for the Single 8 system that were capable of directly recording to pre-striped film which was presented in an oversize Single-8 cartridge which provided access for the camera's sound recording head in a similar manner to Super 8.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The only difference was that film manufacturers initially had to manufacture the film with a rebated area for the sound stripe.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] This was because the pressure plate ensuring good film registration was part of the camera and not the cartridge.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The sound film had to be the same overall thickness as silent film which the camera could also accept.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Although the rebated stock was more expensive to manufacture, a balance stripe on the opposite side of the film was rendered unnecessary and offset the cost.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Fuji later developed a thinner film that did not require rebating, but the balance stripe was required because the thickness of the sound stripe was almost the same as the film base.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] A number of camera companies offered single-width 8 mm film in magazines or spools, but the format faded when Kodak introduced Kodachrome, as this was only available in the Double 8 mm format.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The first single-run 8 mm film was offered in 1935 with a Bell & Howell movie camera Filmo 127-A called Straight Eight.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Single-width 8 mm film revived in the United States by Bolsey-8 in 1956 and continued for some time outside the United States, with Germany Agfa Movex 8 between 1937 and 1950s and Soviet Union KOMZ Ekran movie cameras and Svema offering reversal film in 1960s.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Introduced in 2011 by Nicholas Kovats and implemented by Jean-Louis Seguin, this format uses Standard 8 film in a modified Bolex (H16 or H8) camera.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Similar to the Techniscope cameras of the 1960s, UltraPan 8 achieves wider aspect ratios generally reserved for camera systems with anamorphic lenses through manipulating film negative exposure instead of light capture.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The area of film exposed per frame is 10.52 mm × 3.75 mm, having an aspect ratio of 2.8:1.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] There are effectively two UP8 frames for every one 16 mm frame.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The design means there is no waste of film emulsion for the targeted aspect ratio.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] Earlier versions of this general idea date from the 1950s and exactly the same design occurs in implementations of the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cinematography/8-mm-film] The current implementation of the idea gains impetus from the relative ease with which digital delivery systems can handle what would otherwise have required, in the past, either a dedicated mechanical projector or the transfer to another film format for which projectors were already available.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Cinematographers use a lens to focus reflected light from objects into a real image that is transferred to some image sensor or light-sensitive material inside the movie camera.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] These exposures are created sequentially and preserved for later processing and viewing as a motion picture.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Capturing images with an electronic image sensor produces an electrical charge for each pixel in the image, which is electronically processed and stored in a video file for subsequent processing or display.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Images captured with photographic emulsion result in a series of invisible latent images on the film stock, which are chemically "developed" into a visible image.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The images on the film stock are projected for viewing in the same motion picture.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Cinematography finds uses in many fields of science and business, as well as for entertainment purposes and mass communication.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the 1830s, three different solutions for moving images were invented based on the concept of revolving drums and disks, the stroboscope by Simon von Stampfer in Austria, the phenakistoscope by Joseph Plateau in Belgium, and the zoetrope by William Horner in Britain.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1845, Francis Ronalds invented the first successful camera able to make continuous recordings of the varying indications of meteorological and geomagnetic instruments over time.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The cameras were supplied to numerous observatories around the world and some remained in use until well into the 20th century.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] William Lincoln patented a device, in 1867 that showed animated pictures called the "wheel of life" or "zoopraxiscope".
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In it moving drawings or photographs were watched through a slit.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] On 19 June 1878, Eadweard Muybridge successfully photographed a horse named "Sallie Gardner" in fast motion using a series of 24 stereoscopic cameras.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The cameras were arranged along a track parallel to the horse's, and each camera shutter was controlled by a tripwire triggered by the horse's hooves.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] They were 21 inches apart to cover the 20 feet taken by the horse stride, taking pictures at one-thousandth of a second.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] At the end of the decade, Muybridge had adapted sequences of his photographs to a zoopraxiscope for short, primitive projected "movies", which were sensations on his lecture tours by 1879 or 1880.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Four years later, in 1882, French scientist Étienne-Jules Marey invented a chronophotographic gun, which was capable of taking 12 consecutive frames a second and recording all the frames of the same picture.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The late nineteenth to the early twentieth centuries brought rise to the use of film not only for entertainment purposes but for scientific exploration as well.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] French biologist and filmmaker Jean Painleve lobbied heavily for the use of film in the scientific field, as the new medium was more efficient in capturing and documenting the behavior, movement, and environment of microorganisms, cells, and bacteria, than the naked eye.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This posed a great inconvenience to the scientific and medical worlds.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The development of film and increased usage of cameras allowed doctors and scientists to grasp a better understanding and knowledge of their projects.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The origins of today's cinema go back to the Lumière brothers, Auguste and Louis, who in 1895 developed a machine called the Cinematographe, which had the ability to capture and show moving images.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The early era of cinema saw rapid innovation.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the early-to-mid-20th Century, filmmakers discovered and applied new methods such as editing, special effects, close-ups, sound, widescreen, color films, and more.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Hollywood began to emerge as the Mecca of the film industry, and many of the famous studios from that time still exist over 100 years later in the early-mid 21st century.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The experimental film *Roundhay Garden Scene*, filmed by Louis Le Prince in Roundhay, Leeds, England, on October 14, 1888, is the earliest surviving motion picture.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] An experimental film camera was developed by British inventor William Friese Greene and patented in 1889.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Dickson, working under the direction of Thomas Alva Edison, was the first to design a successful apparatus, the Kinetograph, patented in 1891.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This camera took a series of instantaneous photographs on standard Eastman Kodak photographic emulsion coated onto a transparent celluloid strip 35 mm wide.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The results of this work were first shown in public in 1893, using the viewing apparatus also designed by Dickson, the Kinetoscope.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Contained within a large box, only one person at a time looking into it through a peephole could view the movie.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the following year, Charles Francis Jenkins and his projector, the Phantoscope, made a successful audience viewing while Louis and Auguste Lumière perfected the Cinématographe, an apparatus that took, printed, and projected film, in Paris in December 1895.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The Lumière brothers were the first to present projected, moving, photographic, pictures to a paying audience of more than one person.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1896, movie theaters were open in France (Paris, Lyon, Bordeaux, Nice, Marseille); Italy (Rome, Milan, Naples, Genoa, Venice, Bologna, Forlì); Brussels; and London.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The chronological improvements in the medium may be listed concisely.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1896, Edison showed his improved Vitascope projector, the first commercially successful projector in the U.S.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Cooper Hewitt invented mercury lamps which made it practical to shoot films indoors without sunlight in 1905.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The first animated cartoon was produced in 1906.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Credits began to appear at the beginning of motion pictures in 1911.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The Bell and Howell 2709 movie camera invented in 1915 allowed directors to make close-ups without physically moving the camera.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] By the late 1920s, most of the movies produced were sound films.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Wide screen formats were first experimented within the 1950s.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] By the 1970s, most movies were color films.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] IMAX and other 70mm formats gained popularity.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Wide distribution of films became commonplace, setting the ground for "blockbusters." Film cinematography dominated the motion picture industry from its inception until the 2010s when digital cinematography became dominant.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Film cinematography is still used by some directors, especially in specific applications or out of fondness for the format.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] From its birth in the 1880s, movies were predominantly monochrome.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Contrary to popular belief, monochrome does not always mean black-and-white; it means a movie shot in a single tone or color.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Since the cost of tinted film bases was substantially higher, most movies were produced in black-and-white monochrome.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Even with the advent of early color experiments, the greater expense of color meant films were mostly made in black-and-white until the 1950s, when cheaper color processes were introduced.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] By the 1960s, color became by far the dominant film stock.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the coming decades, the usage of color film greatly increased, while monochrome films became scarce.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Black-and-white cinematography is a technique used where the images are captured and presented in shades of gray, without color.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This artistic approach has a rich history and has been employed in films throughout cinema's evolution.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] It is a powerful tool that allows filmmakers to emphasize contrast, texture, and lighting, enhancing the visual storytelling experience.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The use of black-and-white cinematography dates back to early cinema when color film was not yet available.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Filmmakers relied on this technique to create visually striking and atmospheric films.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Even with the advent of color film technology, black-and-white cinematography continued to be utilized for artistic and thematic purposes.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Ken Dancyger's book *The Technique of Film and Video Editing: History, Theory, and Practice* provides insights into the historical and theoretical aspects of black-and-white cinematography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Dancyger explores how this technique has been employed, examining its impact on storytelling, mood, and visual aesthetics.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The book delves into the artistic choices and technical considerations involved in creating compelling black-and-white imagery, offering an understanding of the technique.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Black-and-white cinematography allows filmmakers to focus on the interplay of light and shadow, emphasizing the contrast between different elements within a scene.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This technique can evoke a sense of nostalgia, evoke a specific time period, or create a timeless and classic feel.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] By stripping away color, filmmakers can emphasize the composition, shapes, and textures within the frame, enhancing the visual impact.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Notable films that have employed black-and-white cinematography include classics such as *Casablanca* (1942), *Raging Bull* (1980), and *Schindler's List* (1993).
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] These films showcase the power and versatility of black-and-white cinematography in creating emotionally resonant visuals.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Black-and-white cinematography remains a relevant and widely used technique in modern filmmaking.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] It continues to be employed by filmmakers to evoke specific moods, convey a sense of timelessness, and enhance the artistic expression of their stories.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] After the advent of motion pictures, a tremendous amount of energy was invested in the production of photography in natural color.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The invention of the talking picture further increased the demand for the use of color photography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] However, in comparison to other technological advances of the time, the arrival of color photography was a relatively slow process.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Early movies were not actually color movies since they were shot monochrome and hand-colored or machine-colored afterward (such movies are referred to as *colored* and not *color*).
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The earliest such example is the hand-tinted Annabelle Serpentine Dance in 1895 by Edison Manufacturing Company.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Machine-based tinting later became popular.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Tinting continued until the advent of natural color cinematography in the 1910s.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Many black-and-white movies have been colorized recently using digital tinting.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This includes footage shot from both world wars, sporting events and political propaganda.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1902, Edward Raymond Turner produced the first films with a natural color process rather than using colorization techniques.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1909, Kinemacolor was first shown to the public.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1917, the earliest version of Technicolor was introduced.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Eastmancolor was introduced in 1950 and became the color standard for the rest of the century.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the 2010s, color films were largely superseded by color digital cinematography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In digital cinematography, the movie is shot on digital media such as flash storage, as well as distributed through a digital medium such as a hard drive.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The basis for digital cameras are metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) image sensors.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The first practical semiconductor image sensor was the charge-coupled device (CCD), based on MOS capacitor technology.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Following the commercialization of CCD sensors during the late 1970s to early 1980s, the entertainment industry slowly began transitioning to digital imaging and digital video over the next two decades.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The CCD was followed by the CMOS active-pixel sensor (CMOS sensor), developed in the 1990s.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Beginning in the late 1980s, Sony began marketing the concept of "electronic cinematography", utilizing its analog Sony HDVS professional video cameras.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The effort met with very little success.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] However, this led to one of the earliest digitally shot feature movies, *Julia and Julia* (1987).
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In 1998, with the introduction of HDCAM recorders and 1920×1080 pixel digital professional video cameras based on CCD technology, the idea, now re-branded as "digital cinematography", began to gain traction.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Shot and released in 1998, *The Last Broadcast* is believed by some to be the first feature-length video shot and edited entirely on consumer-level digital equipment.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In May 1999, George Lucas challenged the supremacy of the movie-making medium of film for the first time by including footage filmed with high-definition digital cameras in *Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace*.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In late 2013, Paramount became the first major studio to distribute movies to theaters in digital format, eliminating 35mm film entirely.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Since then the demand of movies to be developed onto digital format rather than 35mm has increased significantly.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] As digital technology improved, movie studios began increasingly shifting toward digital cinematography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Since the 2010s, digital cinematography has become the dominant form of cinematography after largely superseding film cinematography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The first film cameras were fastened directly to the head of a tripod or other support, with only the crudest kind of leveling devices provided, in the manner of the still-camera tripod heads of the period.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The earliest film cameras were thus effectively fixed during the shot, and hence the first camera movements were the result of mounting a camera on a moving vehicle.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The first known of these was a film shot by a Lumière cameraman from the back platform of a train leaving Jerusalem in 1896, and by 1898, there were a number of films shot from moving trains.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Although listed under the general heading of "panoramas" in the sales catalogues of the time, those films shot straight forward from in front of a railway engine were usually specifically referred to as "phantom rides".
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Paul had the first real rotating camera head made to put on a tripod, so that he could follow the passing processions of Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee in one uninterrupted shot.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This device had the camera mounted on a vertical axis that could be rotated by a worm gear driven by turning a crank handle, and Paul put it on general sale the next year.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Shots taken using such a "panning" head were also referred to as "panoramas" in the film catalogues of the first decade of the cinema.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This eventually led to the creation of a panoramic photo as well.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The standard pattern for early film studios was provided by the studio which Georges Méliès had built in 1897.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This had a glass roof and three glass walls constructed after the model of large studios for still photography, and it was fitted with thin cotton cloths that could be stretched below the roof to diffuse the direct ray of the sun on sunny days.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The soft overall light without real shadows that this arrangement produced, which also exists naturally on lightly overcast days, was to become the basis for film lighting in film studios for the next decade.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Black-and-white cinematography is a technique used in filmmaking where the images are captured and presented in shades of gray, without color.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This artistic approach has a rich history and has been employed in various films throughout cinema's evolution.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The use of black-and-white cinematography dates back to the early days of cinema when color film was not yet available.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Ken Dancyger's book *The Technique of Film and Video Editing: History, Theory, and Practice* provides valuable insights into the historical and theoretical aspects of black-and-white cinematography.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Dancyger explores how this technique has been employed throughout film history, examining its impact on storytelling, mood, and visual aesthetics.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The book delves into the artistic choices and technical considerations involved in creating compelling black-and-white imagery, offering a comprehensive understanding of the technique.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] There are many types of Cinematography that each differ based on production purpose and process.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] These different types of Cinematography are similar in the sense that they all have the goal of conveying a specific emotion, mood or feeling.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] For each different style however they can often convey different emotions and purposes.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Some examples of different types of Cinematography can be known as Realism.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This style of cinematography aims to create a realistic portrayal of the world, often using natural lighting, handheld cameras, and a documentary-like approach to filming.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Classic Hollywood is a style of cinematography characterized by its use of highly polished, studio-produced films with glamorous sets, bright lighting, and romanticized narratives.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Film Noir is a style of cinematography that is characterized by its use of stark contrast and chiaroscuro lighting, low-key lighting, and a dark, brooding atmosphere.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] It often features crime, mystery, and morally ambiguous characters.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] To convey mood, emotion, narrative and other factors within the shot, cinematography is implemented by using different aspects within a film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Lighting on the scene can affect the mood of a scene or film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Darker shots with less natural light can be gloomy, scary, sad, intense.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Brighter lighting can equate to a happier, exciting, more positive mood.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Camera angle can affect a scene by setting perspective.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] It conveys how characters or the audience see something, and through what angle.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Camera angle can also play an important role by highlighting either a close up detail, or background setting.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] A close up angle can highlight detail on someone's face, while a wider lens can give key information that takes place in the background of a shot.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Camera distance can highlight specific details that can be important to a film shot.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] From very far away, a group of people can all look the same, but once you zoom in very close, the viewer is able to see differences within the population through details like facial expression and body language.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Coloring is similar to lighting, in the way that it plays an important role in setting mood and emotion throughout a shot.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] A color like green can convey balance and peace through scenes of nature.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] A shot with a lot of red can express anger, intensity, passion or love.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] While some of these emotions might not come out intentionally while seeing color, it is a subconscious fact that color within cinematography can have a large effect.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Speed is a vital element in cinematography that can be used in a variety of ways, such as the creation of action, or a sense of movement.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Speed can be further used to slow down time, highlight important moments, and oftentimes build a sense of suspense in a film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Slow motion is a technique which involves filming at a higher frame rate, then playing the footage again at a normal speed.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This creates a slowed-down effect in the film, which can put emphasis on or add fluidity to a scene.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] On the other hand, fast motion is the opposite of slow motion, filming at a lower frame rate and then playing the film back at a normal speed.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This creates a sped-up effect which can help to emphasize passage of time, or create a sense of urgency.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Time lapse is when you take a series of still photographs at a regular interval over a long period of time.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] From here, if you play them back continuously, a sped-up effect is shown.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Time lapses are used most effectively to show things like sunrises, natural movement, or growth.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] They are commonly used to show passage of time in a shorter sequence.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Reverse motion is filming a scene normally, then playing the film in reverse.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] This is usually used to create uncommon/surreal effects, and create unusual scenes.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The various techniques involving speed all can add to a films intensity, vibe, show passage of time, and have many other effects.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Camera movement within a film can play a role in enhancing the visual quality and impact of a film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Cinematography can begin with digital image sensor or rolls of film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Advancements in film emulsion and grain structure provided a wide range of available film stocks.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The selection of a film stock is one of the first decisions made in preparing a typical film production.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Advancements and adjustments to nearly all gauges of film create the "super" formats wherein the area of the film used to capture a single frame of an image is expanded, although the physical gauge of the film remains the same.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Super 8 mm, Super 16 mm, and Super 35 mm all utilize more of the overall film area for the image than their "regular" non-super counterparts.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The larger the film gauge, the higher the overall image resolution clarity and technical quality.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The techniques used by the film laboratory to process the film stock can also offer a considerable variance in the image produced.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] By controlling the temperature and varying the duration in which the film is soaked in the development chemicals, and by skipping certain chemical processes (or partially skipping all of them), cinematographers can achieve very different looks from a single film stock in the laboratory.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Some techniques that can be used are push processing, bleach bypass, and cross processing.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Most of modern cinema uses digital cinematography and has no film stocks , but the cameras themselves can be adjusted in ways that go far beyond the abilities of one particular film stock.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] They can provide varying degrees of color sensitivity, image contrast, light sensitivity and so on.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] One camera can achieve all the various looks of different emulsions.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Digital image adjustments such as ISO and contrast are executed by estimating the same adjustments that would take place if actual film were in use, and are thus vulnerable to the camera's sensor designers perceptions of various film stocks and image adjustment parameters.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Filters, such as diffusion filters or color effect filters, are also widely used to enhance mood or dramatic effects.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Most photographic filters are made up of two pieces of optical glass glued together with some form of image or light manipulation material between the glass.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] In the case of color filters, there is often a translucent color medium pressed between two planes of optical glass.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Color filters work by blocking out certain color wavelengths of light from reaching the film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] With color film, this works very intuitively wherein a blue filter will cut down on the passage of red, orange, and yellow light and create a blue tint on the film.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Filters can be used in front of the lens or, in some cases, behind the lens for different effects.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Certain cinematographers, such as Christopher Doyle, are well known for their innovative use of filters; Doyle was a pioneer for increased usage of filters in movies and is highly respected throughout the cinema world.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Lenses can be attached to the camera to give a certain look, feel, or effect by focus, color, etc.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] As does the human eye, the camera creates perspective and spatial relations with the rest of the world.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] However, unlike one's eye, a cinematographer can select different lenses for different purposes.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Variation in focal length is one of the chief benefits.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The focal length of the lens determines the angle of view and, therefore, the field of view.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Cinematographers can choose from a range of wide-angle lenses, "normal" lenses and long focus lenses, as well as macro lenses and other special effect lens systems such as borescope lenses.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Wide-angle lenses have short focal lengths and make spatial distances more obvious.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] A person in the distance is shown as much smaller while someone in the front will loom large.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] On the other hand, long focus lenses reduce such exaggerations, depicting far-off objects as seemingly close together and flattening perspective.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The differences between the perspective rendering is actually not due to the focal length by itself, but by the distance between the subjects and the camera.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Therefore, the use of different focal lengths in combination with different camera to subject distances creates these different rendering.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Changing the focal length only while keeping the same camera position does not affect perspective but the camera angle of view only.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] A zoom lens allows a camera operator to change his focal length within a shot or quickly between setups for shots.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] As prime lenses offer greater optical quality and are "faster" (larger aperture openings, usable in less light) than zoom lenses, they are often employed in professional cinematography over zoom lenses.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Certain scenes or even types of filmmaking, however, may require the use of zooms for speed or ease of use, as well as shots involving a zoom move.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] As in other photography, the control of the exposed image is done in the lens with the control of the diaphragm aperture.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] For proper selection, the cinematographer needs that all lenses be engraved with T-stop, not f-stop so that the eventual light loss due to the glass does not affect the exposure control when setting it using the usual meters.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] The choice of the aperture also affects image quality (aberrations) and depth of field.
[src:cinematography/cinematography-p01] Focal length and diaphragm aperture affect the depth of field of a scene – that is, how much the background, mid-ground and foreground will be rendered in "acceptable focus" (only one exact plane of the image is in precise focus) on the film or video target.
